{"title_page": "Stan Laurel", "text_new": "{{short description|English actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Stan Laurel\n| image = Stan Laurel c1920.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = Laurel circa 1920\n| birth_name = Arthur Stanley Jefferson\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1890|06|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Ulverston]], [[Lancashire]]<!-- PLEASE do not change to Cumbria: the town was in Lancashire when Laurel was born there -->, England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1965|02|23|1890|06|16|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica, Los Angeles, California]], United States\n| website = {{URL|laurel-and-hardy.com}}\n| occupation = {{hlist|Actor|writer|comedian|entertainer|film director}}\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Lois Neilson]]|1926|1934|end=divorced}}<br>\n{{marriage|Virginia Ruth Rogers|1935|1937|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage||1941|1946|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Vera Ivanova Shuvalova|1938|1940|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Ida Kitaeva Raphael|1946}}\n| domesticpartner = [[Mae Dahlberg|Mae Charlotte Dahlberg]] (1919\u20131925)\n| children = 2\n| signature = Stan Laurel signature.svg\n| years_active = 1906\u20131957\n}}\n\n'''Stan Laurel''' (born '''Arthur Stanley Jefferson'''; 16 June 1890 \u2013 23 February 1965) was an English comic actor, writer, and film director who was part of the comedy duo [[Laurel and Hardy]].<ref>\"Obituary\". ''Variety'', 3 March 1965, p. 69.</ref> He appeared with his comedy partner [[Oliver Hardy]] in 107 short films, feature films, and cameo roles.<ref name=\"Time\"/>\n\nLaurel began his career in [[music hall]], where he developed a number of his standard comic devices, including the [[bowler hat]], the deep comic gravity, and the nonsensical understatement. His performances polished his skills at [[pantomime]] and music hall sketches. He was a member of \"[[Fred Karno]]'s Army\", where he was [[Charlie Chaplin]]'s understudy.<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"McCabe\">McCabe 2005, p. 143. Robson, 2005 Retrieved: 18 June 2012.</ref> He and Chaplin arrived in the United States on the same ship from the United Kingdom with the Karno troupe.<ref name=\"Karno\">{{cite web|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/the-fine-mess-maker-at-home/|title=The Fine Mess-Maker at Home|website=New York Times|date=7 September 2012|last=Cavett|first=Dick|access-date=8 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909022128/http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/the-fine-mess-maker-at-home/|archive-date=9 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Laurel began his film career in 1917 and made his final appearance in 1951. He appeared with his comic partner Oliver Hardy in the film short ''[[The Lucky Dog]]'' in 1921, although they did not become an official team until late 1927.<ref name=\"britannica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Laurel-and-Hardy|title=Laurel and Hardy|access-date=18 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418053902/https://www.britannica.com/topic/Laurel-and-Hardy|archive-date=18 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He then appeared exclusively with Hardy until retiring following his comedy partner's death in 1957.\n\nIn 1960, Laurel was given a Lifetime Achievement Academy Award for his pioneering work in comedy, and he has a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 7021 Hollywood Blvd. Laurel and Hardy ranked top among best double acts and seventh overall in a 2005 UK poll to find the ''Comedians' Comedian''.<ref name=\"Legacy\"/> In 2019, Laurel topped a list of the greatest British comedians compiled by a panel on the television channel [[Gold (UK TV channel)|Gold]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Stan Laurel crowned Britain's greatest comedian |url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2019/05/26/43151/stan_laurel_crowned_britains_greatest_comedian |accessdate=19 October 2019 |work=Chortle.co.uk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019113629/https://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2019/05/26/43151/stan_laurel_crowned_britains_greatest_comedian |archive-date=19 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2009, a bronze statue of the duo was unveiled in Laurel's home town of [[Ulverston]].\n{{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Ulverston's most famous son - geograph.org.uk - 151570.jpg|thumb|left|Plaque at Laurel's birthplace in [[Ulverston]]]]\nArthur Stanley Jefferson was born in his grandparents' house on 16 June 1890 in Argyll Street, [[Ulverston]], [[Lancashire]]<!-- PLEASE do not change to Cumbria: the town was in Lancashire when Laurel was born there -->, to Arthur Jefferson, a theatre manager from [[Bishop Auckland]], and Margaret (n\u00e9e Metcalfe), an actress from Ulverston. He was one of five children.<ref name=\"ODNB\">Midwinter, Eric. [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/37659 \"Laurel, Stan\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924154506/http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/37659 |date=24 September 2015 }} ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography,'' 2006. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref>\n\nHis parents were both active in the theatre and always very busy. In his early years, Laurel spent much time living with his maternal grandmother, Sarah Metcalfe.<ref name=\"McCabe\"/> He attended school at [[King James I Academy|King James I Grammar School]] in [[Bishop Auckland]], [[County Durham]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Stan Laurel's former Bishop Auckland school 'left to rot' | website=[[The Northern Echo]] | date=4 February 2012 | url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/9512813.Stan_Laurel_s_former_Bishop_Auckland_school__left_to_rot_/ | access-date=11 February 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212083244/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/9512813.Stan_Laurel_s_former_Bishop_Auckland_school__left_to_rot_/ | archive-date=12 February 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> and the [[Kings Priory School|King's School]] in [[Tynemouth]], [[Northumberland]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Stan Laurel letter set to go under the hammer | website=[[The Northern Echo]] | date=13 September 2014 | url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/southdurham/bishopauckland/11471926.Stan_Laurel_letter_set_to_go_under_the_hammer/ | access-date=11 February 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212083310/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/southdurham/bishopauckland/11471926.Stan_Laurel_letter_set_to_go_under_the_hammer/ | archive-date=12 February 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Stan Laurel plaque at Britannia Music Hall, Glasgow.jpg|thumb|upright|Stan Laurel plaque, [[Britannia Music Hall]], Glasgow]]\nHe moved with his parents to [[Glasgow]], Scotland, where he completed his education at [[Stonelaw High School|Rutherglen Academy]]. His father managed Glasgow's [[The Metropole Theatre|Metropole Theatre]], where Laurel began work. His boyhood hero was [[Dan Leno]], one of the greatest English [[music hall]] comedians.<ref name=\"McCabe\"/> With a natural affinity for the theatre, Laurel gave his first professional performance on stage at the [[Britannia Music Hall|Panopticon]] in [[Glasgow]] at the age of sixteen, where he polished his skills at [[pantomime]] and music hall sketches.<ref>Bowers 2007, pp. 143\u2013147.</ref> It was the music hall from where he drew his standard comic devices, including his [[bowler hat]] and nonsensical understatement.<ref name=\"McCabe\"/>\n\nIn 1912 Laurel worked together with [[Ted Desmond]]\non tour in Netherlands and Belgium as a comedy double act known as the Barto Bros. Their act, which involved them dressing as Romans, finished when Laurel was offered a spot in an American touring troupe. After Laurel left England for America the pair maintained a life-long friendship, sending letters and photos that documented Laurel\u2019s rise from an unknown British comedy actor in 1913 to one of the biggest names in Hollywood in the 1950s. The correspondence, spanning around 50 years and including photos of them being reunited in the US, was put up for auction by Mr Desmond's grandson Geoffrey Nolan in 2018.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/another-fine-missive-stan-laurel-s-letters-on-sale-6r682sg0d</ref><ref>https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/stan-laurels-little-known-comedy-12098175.amp</ref>\n\nHe joined [[Fred Karno]]'s troupe of actors in 1910 with the stage name of \"Stan Jefferson\"; the troupe also included a young [[Charlie Chaplin]]. The music hall nurtured him, and he acted as Chaplin's [[understudy]] for some time.<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"McCabe\"/> Karno was a pioneer of [[slapstick]], and in his biography Laurel stated, \"Fred Karno didn't teach Charlie [Chaplin] and me all we know about comedy. He just taught us most of it\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burton|first1=Alan|title=Pimple, pranks & pratfalls: British film comedy before 1930|date=2000|publisher=Flicks Books|page=51}}</ref> Chaplin and Laurel arrived in the United States on the same ship from Britain with the Karno troupe and toured the country.<ref name=\"Karno\"/>\nDuring the [[First World War]], Laurel registered for military service in America on 5 June 1917, as required under the [[Selective Service Act of 1917|Selective Service Act]]. He was not called up; his registration card states [[Alien (law)|resident alien]] and deafness as exemptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-early-01.html|title=Letters From Stan \u2013 1915\u20131923|first=Bernie|last=Hogya|website=www.lettersfromstan.com|access-date=28 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220140456/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-early-01.html|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebrainydeafsite.com/p3.html|title=P.3|website=TheBrainyDeafSite|access-date=28 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713121725/http://www.thebrainydeafsite.com/p3.html|archive-date=13 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:The Lucky Dog (1921).webm|thumb|left|Laurel and Hardy appeared for the first time together in ''[[The Lucky Dog]]''.]]\n\nThe Karno troupe broke up in the spring of 1914. Stan joined with two other former Karno performers, [[Edgar Hurley]] and his wife Ethel (known as \u201cWren\u201d)to form \u201cThe Three Comiques\u201d.  On the advice of booking agent [[Gordon Bostock]], they call themselves \"the Keystone Trio\". Stan started to do his character as an imitation of Charlie Chaplin, and the Hurleys began to do their parts as silent comedians [[Chester Conklin]] and [[Mabel Normand]]. They played successfully from February through October 1915, until the Hurleys and Stan parted ways. \n<ref>https://www.cinema.ucla.edu/support/stan-laurels-life-laughter</ref>\nBetween 1916 and 1918, he teamed up with Alice Cooke and [[Baldwin Cooke]], who became his lifelong friends to form the \u201cthe Stan Jefferson Trio\u201d. \n\nAmongst other performers, Laurel worked briefly alongside [[Oliver Hardy]] in the silent film short ''[[The Lucky Dog]]'' (1921),<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> before the two were a team. It was around this time that Laurel met [[Mae Dahlberg]]. Around the same time, he adopted the stage name of Laurel at Dahlberg's suggestion that his stage name Stan Jefferson was unlucky, due to it having thirteen letters.{{#tag:ref|Laurel disputed this and claimed that it just \"sounded good\".<ref>McCabe 1961, p. 18.</ref>|group=N}} The pair were performing together when Laurel was offered $75 a week to star in two-reel comedies. After making his first film ''[[Nuts in May (film)|Nuts in May]]'', [[Universal Studios|Universal]] offered him a contract. The contract was soon cancelled during a reorganisation at the studio. Among the films in which Dahlberg and Laurel appeared together was the 1922 parody ''[[Mud and Sand]]''.\n\nBy 1924, Laurel had given up the stage for full-time film work, under contract with [[Joe Rock]] for 12 two-reel comedies. The contract had one unusual stipulation: that Dahlberg was not to appear in any of the films. Rock thought that her temperament was hindering Laurel's career. In 1925, she started interfering with Laurel's work, so Rock offered her a cash settlement and a one-way ticket back to her native [[Australia]], which she accepted.<ref>Bergan 1992, p. 33.</ref> The 12 two-reel comedies were ''[[Mandarin Mix-Up]]'' (1924), ''[[Detained (film)|Detained]]'' (1924), ''[[Monsieur Don't Care]]'' (1924), ''[[West of Hot Dog]]'' (1924), ''[[Somewhere in Wrong]]'' (1925), ''[[Twins (1925 film)|Twins]]'' (1925), ''[[Pie-Eyed]]'' (1925), ''[[The Snow Hawk]]'' (1925), ''[[Navy Blue Days]]'' (1925), ''[[The Sleuth (1925 film)|The Sleuth]]'' (1925), ''[[Dr. Pyckle and Mr. Pryde]]'' (1925) and ''[[Half a Man (film)|Half a Man]]'' (1925).\n\n==Laurel and Hardy==\n{{Main|Laurel and Hardy}}\n[[File:Laurel and Hardy in Lucky Dog.jpg|thumb|left|Laurel with Hardy in ''[[The Lucky Dog (1921 film)|The Lucky Dog]]'' (1921), long before they became a team.]]\nLaurel next signed with the [[Hal Roach]] studio, where he began directing films, including a 1926 production called ''[[Yes, Yes, Nanette]]'' (in which [[Oliver Hardy]] had a part under the name \"Babe\" Hardy). It had been his intention to work primarily as a writer and director.\n\nThe same year, Hardy, a member of the Hal Roach Studios Comedy ''All Star'' players, was injured in a kitchen mishap and hospitalised. Because he was unable to work on the scheduled film, ''Get 'Em Young'', Laurel was asked to return to acting to fill in. Starting early in 1927, Laurel and Hardy began sharing the screen in several short films, including ''[[Duck Soup (1927 film)|Duck Soup]]'', ''[[Slipping Wives]]'' and ''[[With Love and Hisses]]''. The two became friends and their comic chemistry soon became obvious. Roach Studios' supervising director [[Leo McCarey]] noticed the audience reaction to them and began teaming them, leading to the creation of the ''[[Laurel and Hardy]]'' series later that year.\n\nTogether, the two men began producing a huge body of short films, including ''[[The Battle of the Century]]'', ''[[Should Married Men Go Home?]]'', ''[[Two Tars]]'', ''[[Be Big!]]'', ''[[Big Business (1929 film)|Big Business]]'', and many others. Laurel and Hardy successfully made the transition to talking films with the short ''[[Unaccustomed As We Are]]'' in 1929. They also appeared in their first feature in one of the revue sequences of ''[[The Hollywood Revue of 1929]],'' and the following year they appeared as the comic relief in the lavish all-colour (in [[Technicolor]]) musical feature ''[[The Rogue Song]]''. Their first starring feature ''[[Pardon Us]]'' was released in 1931. They continued to make both features and shorts until 1935, including their 1932 three-reeler ''[[The Music Box (film)|The Music Box]],'' which won an [[Academy Award for Live Action Short Film|Academy Award for Best Short Subject]].\n\n===Trouble at Roach Studio===\nDuring the 1930s, Laurel was involved in a dispute with Hal Roach which resulted in the termination of his contract. Roach maintained separate contracts for Laurel and Hardy that expired at different times, so Hardy remained at the studio and was \"teamed\" with [[Harry Langdon]] for the 1939 film ''[[Zenobia (film)|Zenobia]]''. The studio discussed a series of films co-starring Hardy with [[Patsy Kelly]] to be called \"The Hardy Family.\" But Laurel sued Roach over the contract dispute. Eventually, the case was dropped and Laurel returned to Roach. The first film that [[Laurel and Hardy]] made after Laurel returned was ''[[A Chump at Oxford]]''. Subsequently, they made ''[[Saps at Sea]]'', which was their last film for Roach.\n\n===Second World War===\n[[File:Stan in color.jpg|thumb|upright|Stan Laurel in a still from ''[[The Tree in a Test Tube]]'' (1943), a colour short made for the US Department of Agriculture]]\nIn 1941, [[Laurel and Hardy]] signed a contract at [[Twentieth Century-Fox|20th Century-Fox]] to make ten films over five years. Laurel found, to his shock, that he and Hardy were hired only as actors, and were not expected to contribute to the staging, writing, or editing of the productions. When the films proved very successful, Laurel and Hardy were granted more freedom and gradually added more of their own material. They had made six Fox features when the studio suddenly abandoned [[B-picture]] production in December 1944. The team had signed another contract with [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] in 1942, resulting in two more features.<ref>[[Scott MacGillivray|MacGillivray, Scott]]. ''Laurel & Hardy: From the Forties Forward''. Second edition: New York: iUniverse, 2009 {{ISBN|978-1440172397}}; first edition: Lanham, Maryland: Vestal Press, 1998.</ref>\n\nRevisiting his [[music hall]] days, Laurel returned to England in 1947 when he and Hardy went on a six-week tour of the United Kingdom performing in [[variety shows]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tea and buns with Laurel and Hardy: Derek Malcolm on the day he met his comedy heroes|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/oct/11/tea-and-buns-with-laurel-and-hardy-the-day-i-met-my-comedy-heroes|accessdate=12 November 2018|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112101245/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/oct/11/tea-and-buns-with-laurel-and-hardy-the-day-i-met-my-comedy-heroes|archive-date=12 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Mobbed wherever they went, Laurel's homecoming to [[Ulverston]] took place in May, and the duo were greeted by thousands of fans outside the Coronation Hall.<ref name=\"nwmail\"/> The ''[[North-West Evening Mail|Evening Mail]]'' noted: \"Oliver Hardy remarked to our reporter that Stan had talked about Ulverston for the past 22 years and he thought he had to see it.\"<ref name=\"nwmail\">[http://www.nwemail.co.uk/memories/stan-at-queen-s-first-royal-variety-show-1.1015949 \"Stan at Queen's first Royal Variety Show\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201221344/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/memories/stan-at-queen-s-first-royal-variety-show-1.1015949 |date=1 February 2014 }}. ''North West Evening Mail''.</ref> The tour included a ''[[Royal Variety Performance]]'' in front of King [[George VI]] and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]] in London.<ref name=\"nwmail\"/> The success of the tour led them to spend the next seven years touring the UK and Europe.\n\nAround this time, Laurel found out that he had diabetes, so he encouraged Hardy to find solo projects, which he did, taking parts in [[John Wayne]] and [[Bing Crosby]] films.\n\nIn 1950, Laurel and Hardy were invited to France to make a feature film. The film was a disaster, a Franco-Italian co-production titled ''[[Atoll K]]''. (The film was entitled ''Utopia'' in the US and ''Robinson Crusoeland'' in the UK.) Both stars were noticeably ill during the filming. Upon returning to the United States, they spent most of their time recovering. In 1952, Laurel and Hardy toured Europe successfully, and they returned in 1953 for another tour of the continent. During this tour, Laurel fell ill and was unable to perform for several weeks.<ref>Bergen 1992, p. 118.</ref>\n\nIn May 1954, Hardy had a heart attack and cancelled the tour. In 1955, they were planning to do a television series called ''Laurel and Hardy's Fabulous Fables'' based on children's stories. The plans were delayed after Laurel suffered a [[stroke]] on 25 April 1955, from which he recovered. But as the team was planning to get back to work, his partner Hardy had a massive stroke on 14 September 1956, which resulted in his being unable to return to acting.\n\n===Hardy's death===\nOliver Hardy died on 7 August 1957. Laurel was too ill to attend his funeral and said, \"Babe would understand\".<ref name=\"Time\">Rawlngs, Nate. [http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2005073_2005072_2005121,00.html \"Top 10 Across-the-Pond Duos\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821083423/http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2005073_2005072_2005121,00.html |date=21 August 2013 }}, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', 20 July 2010. Retrieved: 18 June 2012.</ref>{{dead link|date=January 2020}} People who knew Laurel said that he was devastated by Hardy's death and never fully recovered from it. He refused to perform on stage or act in another film without his friend,<ref name=\"Time\"/> although he continued to socialise with his fans.\n\n==After Laurel and Hardy==\nIn 1961, Stan Laurel was given a Lifetime Achievement Academy Award for his pioneering work in comedy. He had achieved his lifelong dream as a comedian and had been involved in nearly 190 films. He lived his final years in a small flat in the Oceana Apartments in [[Santa Monica, California]].<ref>[http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan_oceana.html \"Latter.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228174300/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan_oceana.html |date=28 February 2012 }} ''The Stan Laurel Correspondence Archive Project''. Retrieved: 8 September 2012.</ref>\n\nLaurel was always gracious to fans and spent much time answering fan mail. His phone number was listed in the telephone directory, and fans were amazed that they could dial the number and speak to him directly.\n\n[[Jerry Lewis]] was among the numerous comedians to visit Laurel, who offered suggestions for Lewis' production of ''[[The Bellboy]]'' (1960). Lewis paid tribute to Laurel by naming his main character Stanley in the film, and having [[Bill Richmond (writer)|Bill Richmond]] play a version of Laurel as well.<ref>Brody, Richard. [http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/movies/2011/05/jerry-lewis-writer.html \"Front Row: Jerry Lewis, Writer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022103729/http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/movies/2011/05/jerry-lewis-writer.html |date=22 October 2012 }}, ''New Yorker,'' 5 May 2011. Retrieved 17 May 2011.</ref> [[Dick Van Dyke]] told a similar story. When he was just starting his career, he looked up Laurel's phone number, called him, and then visited him at his home. Van Dyke played Laurel on \"The Sam Pomerantz Scandals\" episode of ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]''.\n\nLaurel was offered a cameo role in ''[[It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World]]'' (1963), but turned it down. He did not want to be on screen in his old age,<ref name=\"Karno\"/> especially without Hardy. The cameo appearance was then given to [[Jack Benny]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLaurel and [[Mae Dahlberg]] never married but lived together as common-law husband and wife from 1919 to 1925, before Dahlberg accepted a one-way ticket from [[Joe Rock]] to go back to her native Australia.<ref>Simon Louvish, ''Stan and Ollie, The Roots of Comedy'', Faber & Faber 2001 {{ISBN|0-571-21590-4}}</ref> In November 1937, Dahlberg was back in the US and sued Laurel for financial support. At the time, Laurel's second marriage was in the process of a divorce, with Dahlberg's legal suit adding to Laurel's woes. The matter was settled out of court.<ref>[https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBS19371207.1.4 ''San Bernardino Sun'', Volume 44, 7 December 1937, Page 4, \"Stan Laurels in Agreement\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827165914/https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBS19371207.1.4 |date=27 August 2017 }} Accessed 15 April 2017.</ref> Dahlberg was described as a \"relief project worker\" by the court. Laurel was one of several popular British actors in Hollywood who never became naturalised US citizens.<ref>Prolgue: The Journal of the National Archives, p. 258. Washington, D.C., 1989</ref>\n\nLaurel had four wives and married one of them a second time after their divorce.<ref name=\"latimes.com\">Harnisch, Larry. [http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-then21-2009jun21,0,3596284.story?track=rss \"Stan Laurel's stormy marriage full of off-screen drama.\"] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', 21 June 2009. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref> His first wife was [[Lois Neilson]], whom he married on 13 August 1926. Their daughter Lois was born on 10 December 1927 during the early years of Laurel and Hardy's partnership. In May 1930, their son Stanley was born two months premature and died after nine days. Laurel's daughter Lois died on 27 July 2017, aged 89.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lois-laurel-hawes-dead-stan-laurels-daughter-was-89-1025214 |title=Lois Laurel Hawes, Daughter of Stan Laurel, Dies at 89 |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809173457/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lois-laurel-hawes-dead-stan-laurels-daughter-was-89-1025214 |archive-date=9 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Laurel and Neilson divorced in December 1934.\n\nIn 1935, Laurel married Virginia Ruth Rogers (known as Ruth). In 1937, he filed for divorce, confessing that he was not over his ex-wife Lois, but Lois decided against a reconciliation. On New Year's Day 1938, Laurel married Vera Ivanova Shuvalova (known as Illeana), and Ruth accused him of bigamy, but their divorce had been finalised a couple of days before his new marriage. The new marriage was very volatile, and Illeana accused him of trying to bury her alive in the backyard of their San Fernando Valley home.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harnisch|first1=Larry|title=Stormy marriage full of off-screen drama for Stan Laurel|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jun/21/local/me-then21|accessdate=14 April 2018|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=21 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726193035/http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jun/21/local/me-then21|archive-date=26 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He and Illeana separated in 1939 and divorced in 1940, with Illeana surrendering all claim to the Laurel surname on 1 February 1940 in exchange for $6,500.<ref>Associated Press, \"Surrenders Her Name\", ''The Spokesman-Review'', Spokane, Washington, Friday 2 February 1940, Volume 57, Number 264, page 2.</ref> In 1941, Laurel remarried Virginia Ruth Rogers; they were divorced for the second time in early 1946.<ref name=\"latimes.com\"/> On 6 May 1946, he married Ida Kitaeva Raphael to whom he remained married until his death.<ref name=\"latimes.com\"/>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Laurel grave.JPG|thumb|right|Stan Laurel's grave at Forest Lawn]]\nLaurel was a heavy smoker until suddenly quitting around 1960.<ref>[http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-1964-04.html \"Correspondence: April 4\u201329, 1964.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711221112/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-1964-04.html |date=11 July 2018 }} ''The Stan Laurel Correspondence Project'' via ''lettersfromstan.com.'' Retrieved: 29 September 2018.</ref> In January 1965, he underwent a series of x-rays for an infection on the roof of his mouth.<ref>[http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-1965-01.html \"Correspondence: January 4\u201329, 1965.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903154327/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan_1965-01.html |date=3 September 2011 }} ''The Stan Laurel Correspondence Project'' via ''lettersfromstan.com.'' Retrieved: 10 August 2011.</ref> He died on 23 February 1965, aged 74, four days after suffering a heart attack on 19 February.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1965/02/24/archives/stan-laurel-dies-i-movie-comedian-teamed-with-oliver-hardy-in-200.html \"Stan Laurel Dies. Teamed With Oliver Hardy in 200 Slapstick Films-Played 'Simple' Foil.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723214640/https://www.nytimes.com/1965/02/24/archives/stan-laurel-dies-i-movie-comedian-teamed-with-oliver-hardy-in-200.html |date=23 July 2018 }} ''The New York Times'', 24 February 1965. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref> Minutes before his death, he told his nurse that he would not mind going skiing, and she replied that she was not aware that he was a skier. \"I'm not,\" said Laurel, \"I'd rather be doing that than this!\" A few minutes later he died quietly in his armchair.<ref>Bergen 1992, pp. 119\u2013120.</ref>\n\nAt his funeral, [[Buster Keaton]] said, \"[[Charlie Chaplin|Chaplin]] wasn't the funniest. I wasn't the funniest; this man was the funniest.\" [[Dick Van Dyke]] gave the eulogy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rTw0TPv6n1s|title=Raw footage of Stan Laurels funeral with Dick Van Dyke, Buster Keaton and more|last=ebonyivorymovies|date=2 January 2014|via=YouTube|access-date=12 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609174226/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rTw0TPv6n1s|archive-date=9 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> as a friend, prot\u00e9g\u00e9, and occasional impressionist of Laurel during his later years; he read \"[[The Clown's Prayer]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZRvfn1BCoHwC&pg=PT141&lpg=PT141&dq=Dick+Van+Dyke+a+prayer+for+clowns&source=bl&ots=f-0S_HsdgQ&sig=a3U2zAnu47IevPc7L1CqovPwM0M&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9_dDlrdbQAhUFwiYKHfEHB1sQ6AEIPzAG#v=onepage&q=Dick+Van+Dyke+a+prayer+for+clowns&f=false|title=My Lucky Life in and Out of Show Business: A Memoir|first=Dick Van|last=Dyke|date=3 May 2011|publisher=Crown/Archetype|via=Google Books}}</ref> Laurel had quipped, \"If anyone at my funeral has a long face, I'll never speak to him again.\"<ref name=\"Legacy\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=-h3-oAEoQMYC&pg=PA95 \"The Making of Stan Laurel: Echoes of a British Boyhood\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627191441/http://books.google.com/books?id=-h3-oAEoQMYC&pg=PA95 |date=27 June 2014 }}, p. 95. McFarland, 2011.</ref> He was interred in [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)|Forest Lawn\u2013Hollywood Hills Cemetery]].<ref>Wilson, Scott. ''Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons'', 3d ed.: 2 (Kindle Locations 26901-26907). McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers. Kindle Edition.</ref>\n\n==Legacy and honours==\n[[File:Statues of Stan Laurel and Oliver Hardy.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Statue of Stan Laurel and [[Oliver Hardy]] outside the Coronation Hall, [[Ulverston]], Cumbria, England]]\nLaurel and Hardy are featured on the cover of [[the Beatles]]' 1967 album ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]''.<ref>Levy 2005, p. 5.</ref> In 1989, a statue of Laurel was erected in Dockwray Square, [[North Shields]], [[Tyne and Wear]], England, where he lived at No. 8 from 1897 to 1902. The steps down from the Square to the North Shields Fish Quay were said to have inspired the piano-moving scene in ''[[The Music Box]]''. In a 2005 UK poll, ''Comedians' Comedian'', Laurel and Hardy were ranked top double act, and seventh overall.<ref name=\"Legacy\"/> Along with Hardy, Laurel was inducted into the [[Grand Order of Water Rats]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gowr.co.uk/roll-of-honour/ |title= Roll of Honour |publisher= Grand Order of Water Rats |accessdate= 17 April 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170418162039/http://www.gowr.co.uk/roll-of-honour/ |archive-date= 18 April 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n[[File:Stan Laurel Statue, Bishop Auckland.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Statue of Laurel on the site once occupied by the theatre owned by his parents, in [[Bishop Auckland]], [[County Durham]], north east England]]\n[[Neil Brand]] wrote a radio play entitled ''[[Stan (play)|Stan]]'', broadcast in 2004 on [[BBC Radio 4]] and subsequently on [[BBC Radio 4 Extra]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0076mjl|title=Neil Brand - Stan - BBC Radio 4 Extra|website=BBC|access-date=25 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401162050/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0076mjl|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> starring [[Tom Courtenay]] as Stan Laurel, in which Stan visits Oliver Hardy after Hardy has suffered his stroke and tries to say the things to his dying friend and partner that have been left unsaid. In 2006, [[BBC Four]] showed a drama called ''Stan'', based on Brand's radio play, in which Laurel meets Hardy on his deathbed and reminisces about their career.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/cinema/features/silent-cinema-season.shtml \"BBC Four Cinema - Silent Cinema Season.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060624173712/http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/cinema/features/silent-cinema-season.shtml |date=24 June 2006 }} ''BBC''. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref>\n\nA plaque on the Bull Inn, [[Bottesford, Leicestershire]], England, marks Laurel and Hardy appearing in [[Nottingham]] over Christmas 1952, and staying with Laurel's sister, Olga, who was the landlady of the pub.<ref>[http://leicestershire.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/the-battle-for-bottesford-the-border-town-of-nottinghamshire-and-leicestershire-23520/ \"The Battle for Bottesford \u2013 the border town of Nottinghamshire and Leicestershire.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207081335/http://leicestershire.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/the-battle-for-bottesford-the-border-town-of-nottinghamshire-and-leicestershire-23520 |date=7 December 2010 }} ''Leicestershire Magazine'', 31 July 2010. Retrieved: 6 October 2010.</ref> In 2008, a statue of Stan Laurel was unveiled in [[Bishop Auckland]], [[County Durham]], on the site of the Eden Theatre.<ref>Roberts, Will. [http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/3590723.Laurel_proves_Hardy_after_disaster_delays \"Laurel proves Hardy after disaster delays: Statue of Laurel arrives in Bishop Auckland.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005121533/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/3590723.Laurel_proves_Hardy_after_disaster_delays/ |date=5 October 2012 }} ''thenorthernecho'', 13 August 2008. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref> In April 2009, a bronze statue of Laurel and Hardy was unveiled in Ulverston.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/8006614.stm \"Statue honours Laurel and Hardy.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420073138/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/8006614.stm |date=20 April 2009 }} ''BBC'', 19 April 2009. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/5183293/Hundreds-attend-Laurel-and-Hardy-statue-unveiling.html \"Hundreds attend Laurel and Hardy statue unveiling\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225221216/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/5183293/Hundreds-attend-Laurel-and-Hardy-statue-unveiling.html |date=25 December 2017 }}, ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved: 25 July 2012.</ref>\n\n[[File:Laurel and hardy autocorrect.JPG|thumb|upright|Laurel & Hardy Museum in Ulverston]]\nThere is a Laurel and Hardy Museum in Stan's hometown of Ulverston. There are two Laurel and Hardy museums in Hardy's hometown of [[Harlem, Georgia|Harlem]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. One is operated by the town of Harlem, and the other is a private museum owned and operated by Gary Russeth, a Harlem resident.\n\nIn 2013 [[Gail Louw]] and [[Jeffrey Holland (actor)|Jeffrey Holland]] debuted a short one-man play \"...And this is my friend Mr Laurel\" at the [[Camden Fringe]] festival. The play, starring Holland as Laurel, was taken on tour of the UK in 2014 until June 2015.<ref>[http://www.jeffreyholland.co.uk/Jeffrey_Holland/Mr_Laurel.html \"'...And this is my friend Mr Laurel'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150306222553/http://www.jeffreyholland.co.uk/Jeffrey_Holland/Mr_Laurel.html |date=6 March 2015 }}, ''jeffreyholland.co.uk''. Retrieved: 2 March 2015.</ref>\n\nIn the 2018 film ''[[Stan & Ollie]]'', [[Steve Coogan]] portrayed Laurel (a performance which saw him nominated for the [[BAFTA Awards|BAFTA]] for [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor in a Leading Role]]) and [[John C. Reilly]] played Hardy.<ref name=\"Stan & Ollie\">{{cite news|title=Steve Coogan and John C. Reilly will be Laurel and Hardy in Stan & Ollie|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/steve-coogan-john-c-reilly-will-laurel-hardy-stan-ollie/|publisher=Empire magazine|date=18 January 2016|access-date=19 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105173949/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/steve-coogan-john-c-reilly-will-laurel-hardy-stan-ollie/|archive-date=5 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Developed by [[BBC Films]], the film is set in the twilight of their careers, and focuses on their farewell tour of Britain and Ireland's [[variety show|variety]] halls in 1953.\n\n==Filmography==\n* [[Stan Laurel filmography]] (films of Stan Laurel as an actor without Oliver Hardy)\n* [[Laurel and Hardy filmography]] (filmography of Laurel and Hardy together)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portalbar|Biography|Comedy|Film}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=N}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* Bergen, Ronald. ''The Life and Times of Laurel and Hardy.'' New York: Smithmark, 1992. {{ISBN|0-8317-5459-1}}.\n* Bowers, Judith. ''Stan Laurel and Other Stars of the Panopticon: The Story of the Britannia Music Hall''. Edinburgh: Birlinn Ltd, 2007. {{ISBN|1-84158-617-X}}.\n* Louvish, Simon. ''Stan and Ollie: The Roots of Comedy''. London: Faber & Faber, 2001. {{ISBN|0-571-21590-4}}.\n* Marriot, A. J. ''Laurel & Hardy: The British Tours''. Hitchen, Herts, UK: AJ Marriot, 1993. {{ISBN|0-9521308-0-7}}.\n* Levy, Joe, ed. ''Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time''. New York: Wenner Books, 2005. {{ISBN|978-1-932958-61-4}}.\n* [[John McCabe (writer)|McCabe, John]]. ''Babe: The Life of Oliver Hardy''. London: Robson Books Ltd., 2004. {{ISBN|1-86105-781-4}}.\n* McCabe, John. ''Comedy World of Stan Laurel''. London: Robson Books, 2005, First edition 1975. {{ISBN|978-1-86105-780-8}}.\n* McCabe, John. ''Mr. Laurel & Mr. Hardy: An Affectionate Biography.'' London: Robson Books, 2004, First edition 1961, {{ISBN|1-86105-606-0}}.\n* Stone, Rob. ''Laurel or Hardy: The Solo Films of Stan Laurel and Oliver Hardy.'' Temecula, California: Split Reel Books, 1996\n* Okuda, Ted, and James L. Neibaur. ''Stan Without Ollie: The Stan Laurel Solo Films.'' Jefferson, NC: McFarland and Co., 2012\n* Guiles, Fred Lawrence. ''Stan: The Life of Stan Laurel''. New York: Stein and Day., 1980\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Stan Laurel |sopt=t}}\n* {{IMDb name|0491048}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=109430|name=Stan Laurel}}\n* ''[http://www.brentonfilm.com/articles/the-making-of-stan-laurel-echoes-of-a-british-boyhood The Making of Stan Laurel: Echoes of a British Boyhood]'' article at [http://www.brentonfilm.com/ Brenton Film] by Danny Lawrence, Stan Laurel's biographer\n* [http://www.laurel-and-hardy-museum.co.uk/ Laurel and Hardy Museum, Ulverston]\n* [http://www.lettersfromstan.com/ The Stan Laurel Correspondence Archive Project]\n\n{{Laurel and Hardy}}\n{{Academy Honorary Award}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAward LifeAchievement 1960\u20131979}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Laurel, Stan}}\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:Laurel and Hardy|*]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Lancashire]]\n[[Category:British male comedy actors]]\n[[Category:English entertainers]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male silent film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English stunt performers]]\n[[Category:Grand Order of Water Rats members]]\n[[Category:Music hall performers]]\n[[Category:Silent film comedians]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:1890 births]]\n[[Category:1965 deaths]]\n[[Category:Academy Honorary Award recipients]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox contract players]]\n[[Category:Hal Roach Studios actors]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer contract players]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:British expatriate male actors in the United States]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's School, Tynemouth]]\n[[Category:People educated at Stonelaw High School]]\n[[Category:People from Ulverston]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:19th-century English people]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English comedians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Stan Laurel\n| image = Stan Laurel c1920.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = Laurel circa 1920\n| birth_name = Arthur Stanley Jefferson\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1890|06|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Ulverston]], [[Lancashire]]<!-- PLEASE do not change to Cumbria: the town was in Lancashire when Laurel was born there -->, England\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1965|02|23|1890|06|16|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica, Los Angeles, California]], United States\n| website = {{URL|laurel-and-hardy.com}}\n| occupation = {{hlist|Actor|writer|comedian|entertainer|film director}}\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Lois Neilson]]|1926|1934|end=divorced}}<br>\n{{marriage|Virginia Ruth Rogers|1935|1937|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage||1941|1946|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Vera Ivanova Shuvalova|1938|1940|end=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|Ida Kitaeva Raphael|1946}}\n| domesticpartner = Mae Charlotte Dahlberg (1919\u20131925)\n| children = 2\n| signature = Stan Laurel signature.svg\n| years_active = 1906\u20131957\n}}\n\n'''Stan Laurel''' (born '''Arthur Stanley Jefferson'''; 16 June 1890 \u2013 23 February 1965) was an English comic actor, writer, and film director who was part of the comedy duo [[Laurel and Hardy]].<ref>\"Obituary\". ''Variety'', 3 March 1965, p. 69.</ref> He appeared with his comedy partner [[Oliver Hardy]] in 107 short films, feature films, and cameo roles.<ref name=\"Time\"/>\n\nLaurel began his career in [[music hall]], where he developed a number of his standard comic devices, including the [[bowler hat]], the deep comic gravity, and the nonsensical understatement. His performances polished his skills at [[pantomime]] and music hall sketches. He was a member of \"[[Fred Karno]]'s Army\", where he was [[Charlie Chaplin]]'s understudy.<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"McCabe\">McCabe 2005, p. 143. Robson, 2005 Retrieved: 18 June 2012.</ref> He and Chaplin arrived in the United States on the same ship from the United Kingdom with the Karno troupe.<ref name=\"Karno\">{{cite web|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/the-fine-mess-maker-at-home/|title=The Fine Mess-Maker at Home|website=New York Times|date=7 September 2012|last=Cavett|first=Dick|access-date=8 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909022128/http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/09/07/the-fine-mess-maker-at-home/|archive-date=9 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Laurel began his film career in 1917 and made his final appearance in 1951. He appeared with his comic partner Oliver Hardy in the film short ''[[The Lucky Dog]]'' in 1921, although they did not become an official team until late 1927.<ref name=\"britannica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Laurel-and-Hardy|title=Laurel and Hardy|access-date=18 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418053902/https://www.britannica.com/topic/Laurel-and-Hardy|archive-date=18 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He then appeared exclusively with Hardy until retiring following his comedy partner's death in 1957.\n\nIn 1960, Laurel was given a Lifetime Achievement Academy Award for his pioneering work in comedy, and he has a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 7021 Hollywood Blvd. Laurel and Hardy ranked top among best double acts and seventh overall in a 2005 UK poll to find the ''Comedians' Comedian''.<ref name=\"Legacy\"/> In 2019, Laurel topped a list of the greatest British comedians compiled by a panel on the television channel [[Gold (UK TV channel)|Gold]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Stan Laurel crowned Britain's greatest comedian |url=https://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2019/05/26/43151/stan_laurel_crowned_britains_greatest_comedian |accessdate=19 October 2019 |work=Chortle.co.uk |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019113629/https://www.chortle.co.uk/news/2019/05/26/43151/stan_laurel_crowned_britains_greatest_comedian |archive-date=19 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2009, a bronze statue of the duo was unveiled in Laurel's home town of [[Ulverston]].\n{{TOC limit|limit=2}}\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Ulverston's most famous son - geograph.org.uk - 151570.jpg|thumb|left|Plaque at Laurel's birthplace in [[Ulverston]]]]\nArthur Stanley Jefferson was born in his grandparents' house on 16 June 1890 in Argyll Street, [[Ulverston]], [[Lancashire]]<!-- PLEASE do not change to Cumbria: the town was in Lancashire when Laurel was born there -->, to Arthur Jefferson, a theatre manager from [[Bishop Auckland]], and Margaret (n\u00e9e Metcalfe), an actress from Ulverston. He was one of five children.<ref name=\"ODNB\">Midwinter, Eric. [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/37659 \"Laurel, Stan\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924154506/http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/37659 |date=24 September 2015 }} ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography,'' 2006. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref>\n\nHis parents were both active in the theatre and always very busy. In his early years, Laurel spent much time living with his maternal grandmother, Sarah Metcalfe.<ref name=\"McCabe\"/> He attended school at [[King James I Academy|King James I Grammar School]] in [[Bishop Auckland]], [[County Durham]],<ref>{{cite web | title=Stan Laurel's former Bishop Auckland school 'left to rot' | website=[[The Northern Echo]] | date=4 February 2012 | url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/9512813.Stan_Laurel_s_former_Bishop_Auckland_school__left_to_rot_/ | access-date=11 February 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212083244/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/9512813.Stan_Laurel_s_former_Bishop_Auckland_school__left_to_rot_/ | archive-date=12 February 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> and the [[Kings Priory School|King's School]] in [[Tynemouth]], [[Northumberland]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Stan Laurel letter set to go under the hammer | website=[[The Northern Echo]] | date=13 September 2014 | url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/southdurham/bishopauckland/11471926.Stan_Laurel_letter_set_to_go_under_the_hammer/ | access-date=11 February 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212083310/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/southdurham/bishopauckland/11471926.Stan_Laurel_letter_set_to_go_under_the_hammer/ | archive-date=12 February 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Stan Laurel plaque at Britannia Music Hall, Glasgow.jpg|thumb|upright|Stan Laurel plaque, [[Britannia Music Hall]], Glasgow]]\nHe moved with his parents to [[Glasgow]], Scotland, where he completed his education at [[Stonelaw High School|Rutherglen Academy]]. His father managed Glasgow's [[The Metropole Theatre|Metropole Theatre]], where Laurel began work. His boyhood hero was [[Dan Leno]], one of the greatest English [[music hall]] comedians.<ref name=\"McCabe\"/> With a natural affinity for the theatre, Laurel gave his first professional performance on stage at the [[Britannia Music Hall|Panopticon]] in [[Glasgow]] at the age of sixteen, where he polished his skills at [[pantomime]] and music hall sketches.<ref>Bowers 2007, pp. 143\u2013147.</ref> It was the music hall from where he drew his standard comic devices, including his [[bowler hat]] and nonsensical understatement.<ref name=\"McCabe\"/>\n\nIn 1912 Laurel worked together with [[Ted Desmond]]\non tour in Netherlands and Belgium as a comedy double act known as the Barto Bros. Their act, which involved them dressing as Romans, finished when Laurel was offered a spot in an American touring troupe. After Laurel left England for America the pair maintained a life-long friendship, sending letters and photos that documented Laurel\u2019s rise from an unknown British comedy actor in 1913 to one of the biggest names in Hollywood in the 1950s. The correspondence, spanning around 50 years and including photos of them being reunited in the US, was put up for auction by Mr Desmond's grandson Geoffrey Nolan in 2018.<ref>https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/another-fine-missive-stan-laurel-s-letters-on-sale-6r682sg0d</ref><ref>https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/stan-laurels-little-known-comedy-12098175.amp</ref>\n\nHe joined [[Fred Karno]]'s troupe of actors in 1910 with the stage name of \"Stan Jefferson\"; the troupe also included a young [[Charlie Chaplin]]. The music hall nurtured him, and he acted as Chaplin's [[understudy]] for some time.<ref name=\"Time\"/><ref name=\"McCabe\"/> Karno was a pioneer of [[slapstick]], and in his biography Laurel stated, \"Fred Karno didn't teach Charlie [Chaplin] and me all we know about comedy. He just taught us most of it\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Burton|first1=Alan|title=Pimple, pranks & pratfalls: British film comedy before 1930|date=2000|publisher=Flicks Books|page=51}}</ref> Chaplin and Laurel arrived in the United States on the same ship from Britain with the Karno troupe and toured the country.<ref name=\"Karno\"/>\nDuring the [[First World War]], Laurel registered for military service in America on 5 June 1917, as required under the [[Selective Service Act of 1917|Selective Service Act]]. He was not called up; his registration card states [[Alien (law)|resident alien]] and deafness as exemptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-early-01.html|title=Letters From Stan \u2013 1915\u20131923|first=Bernie|last=Hogya|website=www.lettersfromstan.com|access-date=28 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220140456/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-early-01.html|archive-date=20 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebrainydeafsite.com/p3.html|title=P.3|website=TheBrainyDeafSite|access-date=28 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713121725/http://www.thebrainydeafsite.com/p3.html|archive-date=13 July 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:The Lucky Dog (1921).webm|thumb|left|Laurel and Hardy appeared for the first time together in ''[[The Lucky Dog]]''.]]\n\nThe Karno troupe broke up in the spring of 1914. Stan joined with two other former Karno performers, [[Edgar Hurley]] and his wife Ethel (known as \u201cWren\u201d)to form \u201cThe Three Comiques\u201d.  On the advice of booking agent [[Gordon Bostock]], they call themselves \"the Keystone Trio\". Stan started to do his character as an imitation of Charlie Chaplin, and the Hurleys began to do their parts as silent comedians [[Chester Conklin]] and [[Mabel Normand]]. They played successfully from February through October 1915, until the Hurleys and Stan parted ways. \n<ref>https://www.cinema.ucla.edu/support/stan-laurels-life-laughter</ref>\nBetween 1916 and 1918, he teamed up with Alice Cooke and [[Baldwin Cooke]], who became his lifelong friends to form the \u201cthe Stan Jefferson Trio\u201d. \n\nAmongst other performers, Laurel worked briefly alongside [[Oliver Hardy]] in the silent film short ''[[The Lucky Dog]]'' (1921),<ref name=\"ODNB\"/> before the two were a team. It was around this time that Laurel met [[Mae Dahlberg]]. Around the same time, he adopted the stage name of Laurel at Dahlberg's suggestion that his stage name Stan Jefferson was unlucky, due to it having thirteen letters.{{#tag:ref|Laurel disputed this and claimed that it just \"sounded good\".<ref>McCabe 1961, p. 18.</ref>|group=N}} The pair were performing together when Laurel was offered $75 a week to star in two-reel comedies. After making his first film ''[[Nuts in May (film)|Nuts in May]]'', [[Universal Studios|Universal]] offered him a contract. The contract was soon cancelled during a reorganisation at the studio. Among the films in which Dahlberg and Laurel appeared together was the 1922 parody ''[[Mud and Sand]]''.\n\nBy 1924, Laurel had given up the stage for full-time film work, under contract with [[Joe Rock]] for 12 two-reel comedies. The contract had one unusual stipulation: that Dahlberg was not to appear in any of the films. Rock thought that her temperament was hindering Laurel's career. In 1925, she started interfering with Laurel's work, so Rock offered her a cash settlement and a one-way ticket back to her native [[Australia]], which she accepted.<ref>Bergan 1992, p. 33.</ref> The 12 two-reel comedies were ''[[Mandarin Mix-Up]]'' (1924), ''[[Detained (film)|Detained]]'' (1924), ''[[Monsieur Don't Care]]'' (1924), ''[[West of Hot Dog]]'' (1924), ''[[Somewhere in Wrong]]'' (1925), ''[[Twins (1925 film)|Twins]]'' (1925), ''[[Pie-Eyed]]'' (1925), ''[[The Snow Hawk]]'' (1925), ''[[Navy Blue Days]]'' (1925), ''[[The Sleuth (1925 film)|The Sleuth]]'' (1925), ''[[Dr. Pyckle and Mr. Pryde]]'' (1925) and ''[[Half a Man (film)|Half a Man]]'' (1925).\n\n==Laurel and Hardy==\n{{Main|Laurel and Hardy}}\n[[File:Laurel and Hardy in Lucky Dog.jpg|thumb|left|Laurel with Hardy in ''[[The Lucky Dog (1921 film)|The Lucky Dog]]'' (1921), long before they became a team.]]\nLaurel next signed with the [[Hal Roach]] studio, where he began directing films, including a 1926 production called ''[[Yes, Yes, Nanette]]'' (in which [[Oliver Hardy]] had a part under the name \"Babe\" Hardy). It had been his intention to work primarily as a writer and director.\n\nThe same year, Hardy, a member of the Hal Roach Studios Comedy ''All Star'' players, was injured in a kitchen mishap and hospitalised. Because he was unable to work on the scheduled film, ''Get 'Em Young'', Laurel was asked to return to acting to fill in. Starting early in 1927, Laurel and Hardy began sharing the screen in several short films, including ''[[Duck Soup (1927 film)|Duck Soup]]'', ''[[Slipping Wives]]'' and ''[[With Love and Hisses]]''. The two became friends and their comic chemistry soon became obvious. Roach Studios' supervising director [[Leo McCarey]] noticed the audience reaction to them and began teaming them, leading to the creation of the ''[[Laurel and Hardy]]'' series later that year.\n\nTogether, the two men began producing a huge body of short films, including ''[[The Battle of the Century]]'', ''[[Should Married Men Go Home?]]'', ''[[Two Tars]]'', ''[[Be Big!]]'', ''[[Big Business (1929 film)|Big Business]]'', and many others. Laurel and Hardy successfully made the transition to talking films with the short ''[[Unaccustomed As We Are]]'' in 1929. They also appeared in their first feature in one of the revue sequences of ''[[The Hollywood Revue of 1929]],'' and the following year they appeared as the comic relief in the lavish all-colour (in [[Technicolor]]) musical feature ''[[The Rogue Song]]''. Their first starring feature ''[[Pardon Us]]'' was released in 1931. They continued to make both features and shorts until 1935, including their 1932 three-reeler ''[[The Music Box (film)|The Music Box]],'' which won an [[Academy Award for Live Action Short Film|Academy Award for Best Short Subject]].\n\n===Trouble at Roach Studio===\nDuring the 1930s, Laurel was involved in a dispute with Hal Roach which resulted in the termination of his contract. Roach maintained separate contracts for Laurel and Hardy that expired at different times, so Hardy remained at the studio and was \"teamed\" with [[Harry Langdon]] for the 1939 film ''[[Zenobia (film)|Zenobia]]''. The studio discussed a series of films co-starring Hardy with [[Patsy Kelly]] to be called \"The Hardy Family.\" But Laurel sued Roach over the contract dispute. Eventually, the case was dropped and Laurel returned to Roach. The first film that [[Laurel and Hardy]] made after Laurel returned was ''[[A Chump at Oxford]]''. Subsequently, they made ''[[Saps at Sea]]'', which was their last film for Roach.\n\n===Second World War===\n[[File:Stan in color.jpg|thumb|upright|Stan Laurel in a still from ''[[The Tree in a Test Tube]]'' (1943), a colour short made for the US Department of Agriculture]]\nIn 1941, [[Laurel and Hardy]] signed a contract at [[Twentieth Century-Fox|20th Century-Fox]] to make ten films over five years. Laurel found, to his shock, that he and Hardy were hired only as actors, and were not expected to contribute to the staging, writing, or editing of the productions. When the films proved very successful, Laurel and Hardy were granted more freedom and gradually added more of their own material. They had made six Fox features when the studio suddenly abandoned [[B-picture]] production in December 1944. The team had signed another contract with [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] in 1942, resulting in two more features.<ref>[[Scott MacGillivray|MacGillivray, Scott]]. ''Laurel & Hardy: From the Forties Forward''. Second edition: New York: iUniverse, 2009 {{ISBN|978-1440172397}}; first edition: Lanham, Maryland: Vestal Press, 1998.</ref>\n\nRevisiting his [[music hall]] days, Laurel returned to England in 1947 when he and Hardy went on a six-week tour of the United Kingdom performing in [[variety shows]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tea and buns with Laurel and Hardy: Derek Malcolm on the day he met his comedy heroes|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/oct/11/tea-and-buns-with-laurel-and-hardy-the-day-i-met-my-comedy-heroes|accessdate=12 November 2018|work=The Guardian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181112101245/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/oct/11/tea-and-buns-with-laurel-and-hardy-the-day-i-met-my-comedy-heroes|archive-date=12 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Mobbed wherever they went, Laurel's homecoming to [[Ulverston]] took place in May, and the duo were greeted by thousands of fans outside the Coronation Hall.<ref name=\"nwmail\"/> The ''[[North-West Evening Mail|Evening Mail]]'' noted: \"Oliver Hardy remarked to our reporter that Stan had talked about Ulverston for the past 22 years and he thought he had to see it.\"<ref name=\"nwmail\">[http://www.nwemail.co.uk/memories/stan-at-queen-s-first-royal-variety-show-1.1015949 \"Stan at Queen's first Royal Variety Show\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201221344/http://www.nwemail.co.uk/memories/stan-at-queen-s-first-royal-variety-show-1.1015949 |date=1 February 2014 }}. ''North West Evening Mail''.</ref> The tour included a ''[[Royal Variety Performance]]'' in front of King [[George VI]] and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]] in London.<ref name=\"nwmail\"/> The success of the tour led them to spend the next seven years touring the UK and Europe.\n\nAround this time, Laurel found out that he had diabetes, so he encouraged Hardy to find solo projects, which he did, taking parts in [[John Wayne]] and [[Bing Crosby]] films.\n\nIn 1950, Laurel and Hardy were invited to France to make a feature film. The film was a disaster, a Franco-Italian co-production titled ''[[Atoll K]]''. (The film was entitled ''Utopia'' in the US and ''Robinson Crusoeland'' in the UK.) Both stars were noticeably ill during the filming. Upon returning to the United States, they spent most of their time recovering. In 1952, Laurel and Hardy toured Europe successfully, and they returned in 1953 for another tour of the continent. During this tour, Laurel fell ill and was unable to perform for several weeks.<ref>Bergen 1992, p. 118.</ref>\n\nIn May 1954, Hardy had a heart attack and cancelled the tour. In 1955, they were planning to do a television series called ''Laurel and Hardy's Fabulous Fables'' based on children's stories. The plans were delayed after Laurel suffered a [[stroke]] on 25 April 1955, from which he recovered. But as the team was planning to get back to work, his partner Hardy had a massive stroke on 14 September 1956, which resulted in his being unable to return to acting.\n\n===Hardy's death===\nOliver Hardy died on 7 August 1957. Laurel was too ill to attend his funeral and said, \"Babe would understand\".<ref name=\"Time\">Rawlngs, Nate. [http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2005073_2005072_2005121,00.html \"Top 10 Across-the-Pond Duos\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821083423/http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2005073_2005072_2005121,00.html |date=21 August 2013 }}, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', 20 July 2010. Retrieved: 18 June 2012.</ref>{{dead link|date=January 2020}} People who knew Laurel said that he was devastated by Hardy's death and never fully recovered from it. He refused to perform on stage or act in another film without his friend,<ref name=\"Time\"/> although he continued to socialise with his fans.\n\n==After Laurel and Hardy==\nIn 1961, Stan Laurel was given a Lifetime Achievement Academy Award for his pioneering work in comedy. He had achieved his lifelong dream as a comedian and had been involved in nearly 190 films. He lived his final years in a small flat in the Oceana Apartments in [[Santa Monica, California]].<ref>[http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan_oceana.html \"Latter.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228174300/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan_oceana.html |date=28 February 2012 }} ''The Stan Laurel Correspondence Archive Project''. Retrieved: 8 September 2012.</ref>\n\nLaurel was always gracious to fans and spent much time answering fan mail. His phone number was listed in the telephone directory, and fans were amazed that they could dial the number and speak to him directly.\n\n[[Jerry Lewis]] was among the numerous comedians to visit Laurel, who offered suggestions for Lewis' production of ''[[The Bellboy]]'' (1960). Lewis paid tribute to Laurel by naming his main character Stanley in the film, and having [[Bill Richmond (writer)|Bill Richmond]] play a version of Laurel as well.<ref>Brody, Richard. [http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/movies/2011/05/jerry-lewis-writer.html \"Front Row: Jerry Lewis, Writer\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022103729/http://www.newyorker.com/online/blogs/movies/2011/05/jerry-lewis-writer.html |date=22 October 2012 }}, ''New Yorker,'' 5 May 2011. Retrieved 17 May 2011.</ref> [[Dick Van Dyke]] told a similar story. When he was just starting his career, he looked up Laurel's phone number, called him, and then visited him at his home. Van Dyke played Laurel on \"The Sam Pomerantz Scandals\" episode of ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]''.\n\nLaurel was offered a cameo role in ''[[It's a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World]]'' (1963), but turned it down. He did not want to be on screen in his old age,<ref name=\"Karno\"/> especially without Hardy. The cameo appearance was then given to [[Jack Benny]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLaurel and [[Mae Dahlberg]] never married but lived together as common-law husband and wife from 1919 to 1925, before Dahlberg accepted a one-way ticket from [[Joe Rock]] to go back to her native Australia.<ref>Simon Louvish, ''Stan and Ollie, The Roots of Comedy'', Faber & Faber 2001 {{ISBN|0-571-21590-4}}</ref> In November 1937, Dahlberg was back in the US and sued Laurel for financial support. At the time, Laurel's second marriage was in the process of a divorce, with Dahlberg's legal suit adding to Laurel's woes. The matter was settled out of court.<ref>[https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBS19371207.1.4 ''San Bernardino Sun'', Volume 44, 7 December 1937, Page 4, \"Stan Laurels in Agreement\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170827165914/https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SBS19371207.1.4 |date=27 August 2017 }} Accessed 15 April 2017.</ref> Dahlberg was described as a \"relief project worker\" by the court. Laurel was one of several popular British actors in Hollywood who never became naturalised US citizens.<ref>Prolgue: The Journal of the National Archives, p. 258. Washington, D.C., 1989</ref>\n\nLaurel had four wives and married one of them a second time after their divorce.<ref name=\"latimes.com\">Harnisch, Larry. [http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-then21-2009jun21,0,3596284.story?track=rss \"Stan Laurel's stormy marriage full of off-screen drama.\"] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', 21 June 2009. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref> His first wife was [[Lois Neilson]], whom he married on 13 August 1926. Their daughter Lois was born on 10 December 1927 during the early years of Laurel and Hardy's partnership. In May 1930, their son Stanley was born two months premature and died after nine days. Laurel's daughter Lois died on 27 July 2017, aged 89.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lois-laurel-hawes-dead-stan-laurels-daughter-was-89-1025214 |title=Lois Laurel Hawes, Daughter of Stan Laurel, Dies at 89 |access-date=9 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809173457/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/lois-laurel-hawes-dead-stan-laurels-daughter-was-89-1025214 |archive-date=9 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Laurel and Neilson divorced in December 1934.\n\nIn 1935, Laurel married Virginia Ruth Rogers (known as Ruth). In 1937, he filed for divorce, confessing that he was not over his ex-wife Lois, but Lois decided against a reconciliation. On New Year's Day 1938, Laurel married Vera Ivanova Shuvalova (known as Illeana), and Ruth accused him of bigamy, but their divorce had been finalised a couple of days before his new marriage. The new marriage was very volatile, and Illeana accused him of trying to bury her alive in the backyard of their San Fernando Valley home.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harnisch|first1=Larry|title=Stormy marriage full of off-screen drama for Stan Laurel|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jun/21/local/me-then21|accessdate=14 April 2018|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=21 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726193035/http://articles.latimes.com/2009/jun/21/local/me-then21|archive-date=26 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He and Illeana separated in 1939 and divorced in 1940, with Illeana surrendering all claim to the Laurel surname on 1 February 1940 in exchange for $6,500.<ref>Associated Press, \"Surrenders Her Name\", ''The Spokesman-Review'', Spokane, Washington, Friday 2 February 1940, Volume 57, Number 264, page 2.</ref> In 1941, Laurel remarried Virginia Ruth Rogers; they were divorced for the second time in early 1946.<ref name=\"latimes.com\"/> On 6 May 1946, he married Ida Kitaeva Raphael to whom he remained married until his death.<ref name=\"latimes.com\"/>\n\n==Death==\n[[File:Laurel grave.JPG|thumb|right|Stan Laurel's grave at Forest Lawn]]\nLaurel was a heavy smoker until suddenly quitting around 1960.<ref>[http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-1964-04.html \"Correspondence: April 4\u201329, 1964.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711221112/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-1964-04.html |date=11 July 2018 }} ''The Stan Laurel Correspondence Project'' via ''lettersfromstan.com.'' Retrieved: 29 September 2018.</ref> In January 1965, he underwent a series of x-rays for an infection on the roof of his mouth.<ref>[http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan-1965-01.html \"Correspondence: January 4\u201329, 1965.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903154327/http://www.lettersfromstan.com/stan_1965-01.html |date=3 September 2011 }} ''The Stan Laurel Correspondence Project'' via ''lettersfromstan.com.'' Retrieved: 10 August 2011.</ref> He died on 23 February 1965, aged 74, four days after suffering a heart attack on 19 February.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1965/02/24/archives/stan-laurel-dies-i-movie-comedian-teamed-with-oliver-hardy-in-200.html \"Stan Laurel Dies. Teamed With Oliver Hardy in 200 Slapstick Films-Played 'Simple' Foil.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723214640/https://www.nytimes.com/1965/02/24/archives/stan-laurel-dies-i-movie-comedian-teamed-with-oliver-hardy-in-200.html |date=23 July 2018 }} ''The New York Times'', 24 February 1965. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref> Minutes before his death, he told his nurse that he would not mind going skiing, and she replied that she was not aware that he was a skier. \"I'm not,\" said Laurel, \"I'd rather be doing that than this!\" A few minutes later he died quietly in his armchair.<ref>Bergen 1992, pp. 119\u2013120.</ref>\n\nAt his funeral, [[Buster Keaton]] said, \"[[Charlie Chaplin|Chaplin]] wasn't the funniest. I wasn't the funniest; this man was the funniest.\" [[Dick Van Dyke]] gave the eulogy<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rTw0TPv6n1s|title=Raw footage of Stan Laurels funeral with Dick Van Dyke, Buster Keaton and more|last=ebonyivorymovies|date=2 January 2014|via=YouTube|access-date=12 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609174226/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rTw0TPv6n1s|archive-date=9 June 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> as a friend, prot\u00e9g\u00e9, and occasional impressionist of Laurel during his later years; he read \"[[The Clown's Prayer]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZRvfn1BCoHwC&pg=PT141&lpg=PT141&dq=Dick+Van+Dyke+a+prayer+for+clowns&source=bl&ots=f-0S_HsdgQ&sig=a3U2zAnu47IevPc7L1CqovPwM0M&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9_dDlrdbQAhUFwiYKHfEHB1sQ6AEIPzAG#v=onepage&q=Dick+Van+Dyke+a+prayer+for+clowns&f=false|title=My Lucky Life in and Out of Show Business: A Memoir|first=Dick Van|last=Dyke|date=3 May 2011|publisher=Crown/Archetype|via=Google Books}}</ref> Laurel had quipped, \"If anyone at my funeral has a long face, I'll never speak to him again.\"<ref name=\"Legacy\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=-h3-oAEoQMYC&pg=PA95 \"The Making of Stan Laurel: Echoes of a British Boyhood\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627191441/http://books.google.com/books?id=-h3-oAEoQMYC&pg=PA95 |date=27 June 2014 }}, p. 95. McFarland, 2011.</ref> He was interred in [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)|Forest Lawn\u2013Hollywood Hills Cemetery]].<ref>Wilson, Scott. ''Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons'', 3d ed.: 2 (Kindle Locations 26901-26907). McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers. Kindle Edition.</ref>\n\n==Legacy and honours==\n[[File:Statues of Stan Laurel and Oliver Hardy.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Statue of Stan Laurel and [[Oliver Hardy]] outside the Coronation Hall, [[Ulverston]], Cumbria, England]]\nLaurel and Hardy are featured on the cover of [[the Beatles]]' 1967 album ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]''.<ref>Levy 2005, p. 5.</ref> In 1989, a statue of Laurel was erected in Dockwray Square, [[North Shields]], [[Tyne and Wear]], England, where he lived at No. 8 from 1897 to 1902. The steps down from the Square to the North Shields Fish Quay were said to have inspired the piano-moving scene in ''[[The Music Box]]''. In a 2005 UK poll, ''Comedians' Comedian'', Laurel and Hardy were ranked top double act, and seventh overall.<ref name=\"Legacy\"/> Along with Hardy, Laurel was inducted into the [[Grand Order of Water Rats]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gowr.co.uk/roll-of-honour/ |title= Roll of Honour |publisher= Grand Order of Water Rats |accessdate= 17 April 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170418162039/http://www.gowr.co.uk/roll-of-honour/ |archive-date= 18 April 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n[[File:Stan Laurel Statue, Bishop Auckland.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Statue of Laurel on the site once occupied by the theatre owned by his parents, in [[Bishop Auckland]], [[County Durham]], north east England]]\n[[Neil Brand]] wrote a radio play entitled ''[[Stan (play)|Stan]]'', broadcast in 2004 on [[BBC Radio 4]] and subsequently on [[BBC Radio 4 Extra]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0076mjl|title=Neil Brand - Stan - BBC Radio 4 Extra|website=BBC|access-date=25 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401162050/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0076mjl|archive-date=1 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> starring [[Tom Courtenay]] as Stan Laurel, in which Stan visits Oliver Hardy after Hardy has suffered his stroke and tries to say the things to his dying friend and partner that have been left unsaid. In 2006, [[BBC Four]] showed a drama called ''Stan'', based on Brand's radio play, in which Laurel meets Hardy on his deathbed and reminisces about their career.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/cinema/features/silent-cinema-season.shtml \"BBC Four Cinema - Silent Cinema Season.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060624173712/http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcfour/cinema/features/silent-cinema-season.shtml |date=24 June 2006 }} ''BBC''. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref>\n\nA plaque on the Bull Inn, [[Bottesford, Leicestershire]], England, marks Laurel and Hardy appearing in [[Nottingham]] over Christmas 1952, and staying with Laurel's sister, Olga, who was the landlady of the pub.<ref>[http://leicestershire.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/the-battle-for-bottesford-the-border-town-of-nottinghamshire-and-leicestershire-23520/ \"The Battle for Bottesford \u2013 the border town of Nottinghamshire and Leicestershire.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207081335/http://leicestershire.greatbritishlife.co.uk/article/the-battle-for-bottesford-the-border-town-of-nottinghamshire-and-leicestershire-23520 |date=7 December 2010 }} ''Leicestershire Magazine'', 31 July 2010. Retrieved: 6 October 2010.</ref> In 2008, a statue of Stan Laurel was unveiled in [[Bishop Auckland]], [[County Durham]], on the site of the Eden Theatre.<ref>Roberts, Will. [http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/3590723.Laurel_proves_Hardy_after_disaster_delays \"Laurel proves Hardy after disaster delays: Statue of Laurel arrives in Bishop Auckland.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005121533/http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/3590723.Laurel_proves_Hardy_after_disaster_delays/ |date=5 October 2012 }} ''thenorthernecho'', 13 August 2008. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref> In April 2009, a bronze statue of Laurel and Hardy was unveiled in Ulverston.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/8006614.stm \"Statue honours Laurel and Hardy.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420073138/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cumbria/8006614.stm |date=20 April 2009 }} ''BBC'', 19 April 2009. Retrieved: 20 March 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/5183293/Hundreds-attend-Laurel-and-Hardy-statue-unveiling.html \"Hundreds attend Laurel and Hardy statue unveiling\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225221216/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/5183293/Hundreds-attend-Laurel-and-Hardy-statue-unveiling.html |date=25 December 2017 }}, ''The Telegraph''. Retrieved: 25 July 2012.</ref>\n\n[[File:Laurel and hardy autocorrect.JPG|thumb|upright|Laurel & Hardy Museum in Ulverston]]\nThere is a Laurel and Hardy Museum in Stan's hometown of Ulverston. There are two Laurel and Hardy museums in Hardy's hometown of [[Harlem, Georgia|Harlem]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. One is operated by the town of Harlem, and the other is a private museum owned and operated by Gary Russeth, a Harlem resident.\n\nIn 2013 [[Gail Louw]] and [[Jeffrey Holland (actor)|Jeffrey Holland]] debuted a short one-man play \"...And this is my friend Mr Laurel\" at the [[Camden Fringe]] festival. The play, starring Holland as Laurel, was taken on tour of the UK in 2014 until June 2015.<ref>[http://www.jeffreyholland.co.uk/Jeffrey_Holland/Mr_Laurel.html \"'...And this is my friend Mr Laurel'\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150306222553/http://www.jeffreyholland.co.uk/Jeffrey_Holland/Mr_Laurel.html |date=6 March 2015 }}, ''jeffreyholland.co.uk''. Retrieved: 2 March 2015.</ref>\n\nIn the 2018 film ''[[Stan & Ollie]]'', [[Steve Coogan]] portrayed Laurel (a performance which saw him nominated for the [[BAFTA Awards|BAFTA]] for [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Actor in a Leading Role]]) and [[John C. Reilly]] played Hardy.<ref name=\"Stan & Ollie\">{{cite news|title=Steve Coogan and John C. Reilly will be Laurel and Hardy in Stan & Ollie|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/steve-coogan-john-c-reilly-will-laurel-hardy-stan-ollie/|publisher=Empire magazine|date=18 January 2016|access-date=19 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161105173949/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/steve-coogan-john-c-reilly-will-laurel-hardy-stan-ollie/|archive-date=5 November 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Developed by [[BBC Films]], the film is set in the twilight of their careers, and focuses on their farewell tour of Britain and Ireland's [[variety show|variety]] halls in 1953.\n\n==Filmography==\n* [[Stan Laurel filmography]] (films of Stan Laurel as an actor without Oliver Hardy)\n* [[Laurel and Hardy filmography]] (filmography of Laurel and Hardy together)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portalbar|Biography|Comedy|Film}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=N}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* Bergen, Ronald. ''The Life and Times of Laurel and Hardy.'' New York: Smithmark, 1992. {{ISBN|0-8317-5459-1}}.\n* Bowers, Judith. ''Stan Laurel and Other Stars of the Panopticon: The Story of the Britannia Music Hall''. Edinburgh: Birlinn Ltd, 2007. {{ISBN|1-84158-617-X}}.\n* Louvish, Simon. ''Stan and Ollie: The Roots of Comedy''. London: Faber & Faber, 2001. {{ISBN|0-571-21590-4}}.\n* Marriot, A. J. ''Laurel & Hardy: The British Tours''. Hitchen, Herts, UK: AJ Marriot, 1993. {{ISBN|0-9521308-0-7}}.\n* Levy, Joe, ed. ''Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time''. New York: Wenner Books, 2005. {{ISBN|978-1-932958-61-4}}.\n* [[John McCabe (writer)|McCabe, John]]. ''Babe: The Life of Oliver Hardy''. London: Robson Books Ltd., 2004. {{ISBN|1-86105-781-4}}.\n* McCabe, John. ''Comedy World of Stan Laurel''. London: Robson Books, 2005, First edition 1975. {{ISBN|978-1-86105-780-8}}.\n* McCabe, John. ''Mr. Laurel & Mr. Hardy: An Affectionate Biography.'' London: Robson Books, 2004, First edition 1961, {{ISBN|1-86105-606-0}}.\n* Stone, Rob. ''Laure