{"title_page": "National Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa", "text_new": "{{Infobox monument\n| name          = National Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa\n| native_name   = \n| image         = Blackmadonna.jpeg\n| caption       = The Black Madonna of Czestochowa\n| location      = Doylestown, Pennsylvania\n| designer      = George Szeptycki\n| type          = Shrine\n| material      = \n| length        = \n| width         = \n| height        = \n| begin         = 1953\n| complete      = \n| open          = June 26, 1955\n| dismantled    = \n| dedicated_to  = Black Madonna of Cz\u0119stochowa\n| map_image     = \n| map_text      = \n| map_width     = \n| relief        = \n| coordinates   = \n| website       =\n| extra         = \n}}\n\n{{Refimprove|date=July 2019}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:National Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa Main.jpg|350px|thumb|Main Church. {{deletable image-caption|Sunday, 16 August 2009}}]] -->\nThe '''National Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa''' ''(or simply '''Czestochowa''')'', known also as the '''American Czestochowa''' is a [[Polish-American]] [[Roman Catholic]] [[shrine]] near [[Doylestown, Pennsylvania]], founded in 1953. It houses a reproduction of the [[Black Madonna]] [[icon]] of [[Cz\u0119stochowa]], [[Poland]].  The heart of Poland's second prime minister, [[Ignacy Jan Paderewski]], is also preserved there.<ref>[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.org/historical_information/jan_paderewski.html \"Background of Ignacy Jan Paderewski\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051124115344/http://www.arlingtoncemetery.org/historical_information/jan_paderewski.html |date=24 November 2005 }}. [[Arlington National Cemetery]].</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1953 a Polish [[Order of Saint Paul the First Hermit|Pauline]] [[monk]], Father Michael M. Zembrzuski, purchased a tract of land near Doylestown with the intention of building a chapel dedicated to the [[Black Madonna of Cz\u0119stochowa]] at [[Jasna G\u00f3ra]], Poland's most important religious [[icon]], to reconnect Polish-Americans with their Polish Catholic roots. Archbishop [[John Francis O'Hara]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Philadelphia|Philadelphia]] granted permission for the erection of a shrine, and a barn was converted into the first chapel; it was moved to a new site and dedicated on June 26, 1955.<ref>[https://www.czestochowa.us/about-us/history/ \"History\", The National Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa]</ref>\n\nThe chapel was reorganized as a shrine to celebrate the [[History of Poland|thousandth anniversary of the Polish nation]] in 1966. It was dedicated on October 16, 1966, by [[Archbishop]] (later Cardinal) [[John Krol]], with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] and members of his family as honored guests.<ref name=Pronechen/> The centerpiece of the new shrine was a church building designed by the Polish-American architect George Szeptycki housing the replica of the [[Black Madonna]] painting.\n\n[[Pope John Paul II|Cardinal Karol Wojtyla]] visited twice: first in 1969 and then in 1976, while attending the Eucharistic Congress in Philadelphia.<ref name=Pronechen/>\n\nIn subsequent years other facilities have been added to the site, including a Polish-American cemetery (including monuments to Poland's second prime minister [[Ignacy Paderewski]], the Polish-Lithuanian [[hussar]]s, and the victims of the [[Katyn massacre|Katy\u0144]] massacres), a monastery, and a visitor center. The cemetery also includes the graves of members of the [[Polish Veterans of World War II (United States)|Polish Veterans of World War II]]. The lower church interior was remodeled to resemble the interior of the [[Jasna G\u00f3ra]] shrine in Poland housing the original painting. There is also an outdoor pathway with the [[Stations of the Cross]].\n\n==Activities==\nOne of the largest celebrations is the annual feast of Our Lady of Czestochowa on August 26, followed by an annual [[Philadelphia Polish American Festival|Polish Festival]] held every Labor Day weekend.<ref>[https://www.visitbuckscounty.com/listing/national-shrine-of-our-lady-of-czestochowa/229/ \"National Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa\", Visit Bucks County]</ref> Since 1988, there has been an annual pilgrimage from the Church of Ss. Peter and Paul in [[Great Meadows, New Jersey]].<ref>[https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/catholics_to_make_57mile_pilgrimage_to_shrine_of_our_lady_of_Czestochowa \"Catholics to make 57-mile pilgrimage to Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa\", Catholic News Agency, August 7, 2008]</ref> Thousands take part in an outdoor Rosary candlelight procession on October 7, Feast of [[Our Lady of the Rosary]].<ref name=Pronechen>[http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/a-visit-to-the-american-czestochowa Pronechen, Joseph. \"A Visit to the \u2018American Czestochowa\u2019\", ''National Catholic Register'', August 26, 2012]</ref> The shrine is under the direction of the Pauline Fathers and Brothers who also administer the Shrine in Poland.<ref>[http://www.polishamericancenter.org/Czestochowa.htm \"Our Lady of Czestochowa\", Polish American Center]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Black Madonna Shrine, Missouri]]\n*[[List of shrines#United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.czestochowa.us/ Official site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060407042717/http://www.phillyburbs.com/pointsofinterest/shrine/America.htm Article describing the shrine]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Philadelphia|state=collapsed}}\n{{coord|40.3192|-75.1795|region:US-PA_type:landmark|display=title}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic national shrines in the United States]]\n[[Category:Churches in Bucks County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Bucks County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Black Madonna of Cz\u0119stochowa]]\n[[Category:Cz\u0119stochowa]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Madonna and Child]]\n[[Category:Katyn massacre memorials]]\n[[Category:Pauline Order]]\n[[Category:Polish-American culture in Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox monument\n| name          = National Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa\n| native_name   = \n| image         = Blackmadonna.jpeg\n| caption       = The Black Madonna of Czestochowa\n| location      = Doylestown, Pennsylvania\n| designer      = George Szeptycki\n| type          = Shrine\n| material      = \n| length        = \n| width         = \n| height        = \n| begin         = 1953\n| complete      = \n| open          = June 26, 1955\n| dismantled    = \n| dedicated_to  = Black Madonna of Cz\u0119stochowa\n| map_image     = \n| map_text      = \n| map_width     = \n| relief        = \n| coordinates   = \n| website       =\n| extra         = \n}}\n\n{{Refimprove|date=July 2019}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:National Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa Main.jpg|350px|thumb|Main Church. {{deletable image-caption|Sunday, 16 August 2009}}]] -->\nThe '''National Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa''' ''(or simply '''Czestochowa''')'', known also as the '''American Czestochowa''' is a [[Polish-American]] [[Roman Catholic]] [[shrine]] near [[Doylestown, Pennsylvania]], founded in 1953. It houses a reproduction of the [[Black Madonna]] [[icon]] of [[Cz\u0119stochowa]], [[Poland]].  The heart of Poland's second prime minister, [[Ignacy Jan Paderewski]], is also preserved there.<ref>[http://www.arlingtoncemetery.org/historical_information/jan_paderewski.html \"Background of Ignacy Jan Paderewski\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051124115344/http://www.arlingtoncemetery.org/historical_information/jan_paderewski.html |date=24 November 2005 }}. [[Arlington National Cemetery]].</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1953 a Polish [[Order of Saint Paul the First Hermit|Pauline]] [[monk]], Father Michael M. Zembrzuski, purchased a tract of land near Doylestown with the intention of building a chapel dedicated to the [[Black Madonna of Cz\u0119stochowa]] at [[Jasna G\u00f3ra]], Poland's most important religious [[icon]], to reconnect Polish-Americans with their Polish Catholic roots. Archbishop [[John Francis O'Hara]] of Philadelphia granted permission for the erection of a shrine, and a barn was converted into the first chapel; it was moved to a new site and dedicated on June 26, 1955.<ref>[https://www.czestochowa.us/about-us/history/ \"History\", The National Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa]</ref>\n\nThe chapel was reorganized as a shrine to celebrate the [[History of Poland|thousandth anniversary of the Polish nation]] in 1966. It was dedicated on October 16, 1966, by [[Archbishop]] (later Cardinal) [[John Krol]], with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] and members of his family as honored guests.<ref name=Pronechen/> The centerpiece of the new shrine was a church building designed by the Polish-American architect George Szeptycki housing the replica of the [[Black Madonna]] painting.\n\n[[Pope John Paul II|Cardinal Karol Wojtyla]] visited twice: first in 1969 and then in 1976, while attending the Eucharistic Congress in Philadelphia.<ref name=Pronechen/>\n\nIn subsequent years other facilities have been added to the site, including a Polish-American cemetery (including monuments to Poland's second prime minister [[Ignacy Paderewski]], the Polish-Lithuanian [[hussar]]s, and the victims of the [[Katyn massacre|Katy\u0144]] massacres), a monastery, and a visitor center. The cemetery also includes the graves of members of the [[Polish Veterans of World War II (United States)|Polish Veterans of World War II]]. The lower church interior was remodeled to resemble the interior of the [[Jasna G\u00f3ra]] shrine in Poland housing the original painting. There is also an outdoor pathway with the [[Stations of the Cross]].\n\n==Activities==\nOne of the largest celebrations is the annual feast of Our Lady of Czestochowa on August 26, followed by an annual [[Philadelphia Polish American Festival|Polish Festival]] held every Labor Day weekend.<ref>[https://www.visitbuckscounty.com/listing/national-shrine-of-our-lady-of-czestochowa/229/ \"National Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa\", Visit Bucks County]</ref> Since 1988, there has been an annual pilgrimage from the Church of Ss. Peter and Paul in [[Great Meadows, New Jersey]].<ref>[https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/catholics_to_make_57mile_pilgrimage_to_shrine_of_our_lady_of_Czestochowa \"Catholics to make 57-mile pilgrimage to Shrine of Our Lady of Czestochowa\", Catholic News Agency, August 7, 2008]</ref> Thousands take part in an outdoor Rosary candlelight procession on October 7, Feast of [[Our Lady of the Rosary]].<ref name=Pronechen>[http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/a-visit-to-the-american-czestochowa Pronechen, Joseph. \"A Visit to the \u2018American Czestochowa\u2019\", ''National Catholic Register'', August 26, 2012]</ref> The shrine is under the direction of the Pauline Fathers and Brothers who also administer the Shrine in Poland.<ref>[http://www.polishamericancenter.org/Czestochowa.htm \"Our Lady of Czestochowa\", Polish American Center]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Black Madonna Shrine, Missouri]]\n*[[List of shrines#United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.czestochowa.us/ Official site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060407042717/http://www.phillyburbs.com/pointsofinterest/shrine/America.htm Article describing the shrine]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Philadelphia|state=collapsed}}\n{{coord|40.3192|-75.1795|region:US-PA_type:landmark|display=title}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic national shrines in the United States]]\n[[Category:Churches in Bucks County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Bucks County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Black Madonna of Cz\u0119stochowa]]\n[[Category:Cz\u0119stochowa]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Madonna and Child]]\n[[Category:Katyn massacre memorials]]\n[[Category:Pauline Order]]\n[[Category:Polish-American culture in Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Freddiem", "label": "safe", "comment": "appropriate link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Shrine_of_Our_Lady_of_Czestochowa"}
{"title_page": "Antony H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Antony H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen\n| image                 = Antony Hamalainen performing live in Brussels.jpg\n| caption            = H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen performing live with Nightrage, Magasin 4 Brussels, Belgium\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Antony H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen\n| alias               = \n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1980|08|28|mf=y}}\n| death_date                = \n| origin              = [[Finland]]\n| instrument          = [[Vocals]], [[guitar]], [[Bass (guitar)|bass]], [[drums]]\n| genre               = [[Death metal]], [[black metal]], [[melodic death metal]], [[deathgrind]], [[thrash metal]]\n| occupation          = [[Musician]]\n| label               = [[Listenable Records]], [[Lifeforce Records|Lifeforce]], [[Century Media]], [[Prosthetic Records]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Armageddon (Swedish band)|Armageddon]]<br /> [[Nightrage]]<br />[[Amaranthe]]<br />\n|website = {{Instagram|antonyhamalainen}}, {{Facebook|antony.hamalainen}}\n}}\n\n'''Antony H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen''' (born August 28, 1980, in [[H\u00e4meenlinna]], Finland), is a Finnish musician and composer living in the United States.\n\n==Biography==\nIn the early 1990s, he started playing bass, drums, and singing for multiple bands based both in the US and Finland.\n\nSeptember 2007, H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen joined the [[Gothenburg]] based [[melodic death metal]] band [[Nightrage]].\n\nIn 2015, [[Armageddon (Swedish band)|Armageddon]], a [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[melodic death metal]] band led by former [[Arch Enemy]]-guitarist [[Christopher Amott]], announced him as their permanent vocalist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/christopher-amotts-armageddon-taps-ex-nightrage-singer-antony-hamalainen-for-u-s-tour/ |title=Christopher Amott's Armageddon Taps Ex-Nightrage Singer Antony H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen For U.S. Tour |accessdate=2014-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2019/02/05/daughter-chaos-new-single-intergalactic-metal-or-string-quartet/ |title=Daughter Chaos\u2019s New Single \"Intergalactic:\" Metal or Intergalactic String Quartet? |accessdate=2019-02-05}}</ref>\n\nHe occasionally provides guest vocals for bands ranging in all genres of extreme metal both live, and in studio.\n\n==Style==\nIn reference to his work on the Nightrage album [[Wearing A Martyr's Crown]], Sputnikmusic wrote \"''H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen, from Finland, who has a lot of vocal similarities to [[Tomas Lindberg]], which brings back a resemblance to their original sound from their first two albums\". Added to his clean vocals \"he can still maintain a melodic edge, but he only does it every now and again within the album; he only does it for the purpose of giving some of the songs a musical edge so the listener doesn\u2019t fall asleep thinking that the only new addition of style is just a higher use of acoustic guitars.''\" <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/45967/Nightrage-Insidious/ |title=Nightrage-Insidious Album Review |accessdate=2011-10-08}}</ref>\n\n== Live session ==\n*[[Amaranthe]] - vocals, live (September 14, 2012 at [[ProgPower USA|ProgPower]] USA XIII, [[Atlanta, Georgia]], United States)\n\n== Recording Appearances ==\n* ''[[Rusted Eyes Awake]]'' (2008) by [[Landmine Marathon]] - guest vocals on \"Bled To Oblivion\"\n* ''The Essence of Decay'' (2009) by Rising Pain - guest vocals on \"Feel Less Alive\" and \"Am I Awake\"\n* ''Self Destruct Syndrome'' (2011) by Neverborne - guest vocals on \"Mechanical Ruin\"\n* ''Apathy's Throne EP'' (2011) by Nervosia - all vocals\n* ''Of Unsound Minds'' (2012) by AfterBlood (feat. [[Tom Angelripper]]) - guest vocals on \"The More I Lie\"\n* ''The Darkest Of Angels'' (2016) by [[Dead By Wednesday]] - all vocals on \"Defining Fire\"\n* ''The Outsider'' (2016) by The Outsider - all vocals on \"The Race That Failed\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metal-archives.com/albums/The_Outsider/The_Outsider/592337 |title=The Outsider |accessdate=2016-07-14}}</ref>\n* ''Lakewind Whispers EP'' (2017) by Nordj\u00e4rvi - all vocals\n* ''No Longer The Sun Rise'' (2018) by Earthward - all vocals\n* ''Daughter Chaos / Intergalactic (single)'' (2019) by Daughter Chaos - all vocals\n\n== Compilation ==\n* ''Holier Than Thou'' by [[Nightrage]] for [[Metal Hammer]] [[Magazine]], [[Greece]] (on \"And Coverz for All - A Greek Tribute to [[Metallica]]\") - vocals\n\n== Discography ==\n\n===As a member===\n\n=== With Nightrage ===\n* ''[[Wearing A Martyr's Crown]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Insidious (Nightrage album)|Insidious]]'' (2011)\n\n=== With Meridian Dawn ===\n* ''[[The Mixtape EP]]'' (2014)\n\n=== With Armageddon ===\n*''[[Crossing the Rubicon (Revisited)]]'' (2016)\n\n=== With Crystal Tears ===\n* ''Ghostdance (single)'' (2019)\n* ''Nosi Balasi (Filipino Version)'' (2019)\n* ''New Album'' (2020)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.facebook.com/antony.hamalainen Antony H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen Official Facebook]\n\n{{Nightrage}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamalainen, Antony}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from H\u00e4meenlinna]]\n[[Category:Finnish heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Finnish male singers]]\n[[Category:Finnish expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Nightrage members]]\n[[Category:21st-century Finnish singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Antony H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen\n| image                 = Antony Hamalainen performing live in Brussels.jpg\n| caption            = H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen performing live with Nightrage, Magasin 4 Brussels, Belgium\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Antony H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen\n| alias               = \n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1980|08|28|mf=y}}\n| death_date                = \n| origin              = [[Finland]]\n| instrument          = [[Vocals]], [[guitar]], [[Bass (guitar)|bass]], [[drums]]\n| genre               = [[Death metal]], [[black metal]], [[melodic death metal]], [[deathgrind]], [[thrash metal]]\n| occupation          = [[Musician]]\n| label               = [[Listenable Records]], [[Lifeforce Records|Lifeforce]], [[Century Media]], [[Prosthetic Records]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Armageddon (Swedish band)|Armageddon]]<br /> [[Nightrage]]<br />[[Amaranthe]]<br />\n|website = {{Instagram|antonyhamalainen}}, {{Facebook|antony.hamalainen}}\n}}\n\n'''Antony H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen''' (born August 28, 1980, in [[H\u00e4meenlinna]], Finland), is a Finnish musician and composer living in the United States.\n\n==Biography==\nIn the early 1990s, he started playing bass, drums, and singing for multiple bands based both in the USA and Finland.\n\nSeptember 2007, H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen joined the [[Gothenburg]] based [[melodic death metal]] band [[Nightrage]].\n\nIn 2015, [[Armageddon (Swedish band)|Armageddon]], a [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[melodic death metal]] band led by former [[Arch Enemy]]-guitarist [[Christopher Amott]], announced him as their permanent vocalist.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/christopher-amotts-armageddon-taps-ex-nightrage-singer-antony-hamalainen-for-u-s-tour/ |title=Christopher Amott's Armageddon Taps Ex-Nightrage Singer Antony H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen For U.S. Tour |accessdate=2014-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metalsucks.net/2019/02/05/daughter-chaos-new-single-intergalactic-metal-or-string-quartet/ |title=Daughter Chaos\u2019s New Single \"Intergalactic:\" Metal or Intergalactic String Quartet? |accessdate=2019-02-05}}</ref>\n\nHe occasionally provides guest vocals for bands ranging in all genres of extreme metal both live, and in studio.\n\n==Style==\nIn reference to his work on the Nightrage album [[Wearing A Martyr's Crown]], Sputnikmusic wrote \"''H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen, from Finland, who has a lot of vocal similarities to [[Tomas Lindberg]], which brings back a resemblance to their original sound from their first two albums\". Added to his clean vocals \"he can still maintain a melodic edge, but he only does it every now and again within the album; he only does it for the purpose of giving some of the songs a musical edge so the listener doesn\u2019t fall asleep thinking that the only new addition of style is just a higher use of acoustic guitars.''\" <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/45967/Nightrage-Insidious/ |title=Nightrage-Insidious Album Review |accessdate=2011-10-08}}</ref>\n\n== Live session ==\n*[[Amaranthe]] - vocals, live (September 14, 2012 at [[ProgPower USA|ProgPower]] USA XIII, [[Atlanta, Georgia]], United States)\n\n== Recording Appearances ==\n* ''[[Rusted Eyes Awake]]'' (2008) by [[Landmine Marathon]] - guest vocals on \"Bled To Oblivion\"\n* ''The Essence of Decay'' (2009) by Rising Pain - guest vocals on \"Feel Less Alive\" and \"Am I Awake\"\n* ''Self Destruct Syndrome'' (2011) by Neverborne - guest vocals on \"Mechanical Ruin\"\n* ''Apathy's Throne EP'' (2011) by Nervosia - all vocals\n* ''Of Unsound Minds'' (2012) by AfterBlood (feat. [[Tom Angelripper]]) - guest vocals on \"The More I Lie\"\n* ''The Darkest Of Angels'' (2016) by [[Dead By Wednesday]] - all vocals on \"Defining Fire\"\n* ''The Outsider'' (2016) by The Outsider - all vocals on \"The Race That Failed\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metal-archives.com/albums/The_Outsider/The_Outsider/592337 |title=The Outsider |accessdate=2016-07-14}}</ref>\n* ''Lakewind Whispers EP'' (2017) by Nordj\u00e4rvi - all vocals\n* ''No Longer The Sun Rise'' (2018) by Earthward - all vocals\n* ''Daughter Chaos / Intergalactic (single)'' (2019) by Daughter Chaos - all vocals\n\n== Compilation ==\n* ''Holier Than Thou'' by [[Nightrage]] for [[Metal Hammer]] [[Magazine]], [[Greece]] (on \"And Coverz for All - A Greek Tribute to [[Metallica]]\") - vocals\n\n== Discography ==\n\n===As a member===\n\n=== With Nightrage ===\n* ''[[Wearing A Martyr's Crown]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Insidious (Nightrage album)|Insidious]]'' (2011)\n\n=== With Meridian Dawn ===\n* ''[[The Mixtape EP]]'' (2014)\n\n=== With Armageddon ===\n*''[[Crossing the Rubicon (Revisited)]]'' (2016)\n\n=== With Crystal Tears ===\n* ''Ghostdance (single)'' (2019)\n* ''Nosi Balasi (Filipino Version)'' (2019)\n* ''New Album'' (2020)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.facebook.com/antony.hamalainen Antony H\u00e4m\u00e4l\u00e4inen Official Facebook]\n\n{{Nightrage}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamalainen, Antony}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from H\u00e4meenlinna]]\n[[Category:Finnish heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:Finnish male singers]]\n[[Category:Finnish expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Nightrage members]]\n[[Category:21st-century Finnish singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:clean up,typo(s) fixed: the USA \u2192 the US", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antony_H%C3%A4m%C3%A4l%C3%A4inen"}
{"title_page": "Terrorizer", "text_new": "{{for|the UK-based extreme music magazine|Terrorizer (magazine)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Terrorizer\n| image            =\n| caption          =fatt\n| image_size       =\n| background       = group_or_band\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Grindcore]]\n* [[deathgrind]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/metal_hardcore_2012_year_of_grindcore|title=Metal and Hardcore 2012: The Year of Grindcore|website=Exclaim.ca}}</ref>}}\n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| years_active     = {{flatlist|\n* 1986\u20131989\n* 2005\u20132006\n* 2009\u2013present}}\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Earache Records|Earache]]\n* [[Season of Mist]]\n* [[Century Media Records|Century Media]]\n* [[Relativity Records|Relativity]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Morbid Angel]]\n* [[Napalm Death]]\n* [[Nausea (band, Los Angeles)| Nausea LA]]\n* [[Monstrosity (band)|Monstrosity]]}}\n| website          = http://www.terrorizergrindcore.net/\n| current_members  = [[Pete Sandoval]]<br>Sam Molina<br>Lee Harrison\n| past_members     = Oscar Garcia<br>[[Jesse Pintado]]<br>Alfred \"Garvey\" Estrada<br>Tony Norman<br>Anthony Rezhawk<br>Katina Culture<br>[[David Vincent]]\n}}\n\n'''Terrorizer''' is an American [[grindcore]]<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p14469|pure_url=yes}} Terrorizer | AllMusic<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> band formed in 1986 in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], United States. After disbanding, its members gained recognition by playing in influential [[extreme metal]] bands, such as [[Morbid Angel]] ([[David Vincent]], [[Pete Sandoval]]), [[Napalm Death]] ([[Jesse Pintado]]) and [[Nausea (band, Los Angeles)|Nausea]] (Oscar Garcia, Alfred \"Garvey\" Estrada). To date, Terrorizer has released four studio albums, and broken up twice (once in 1989 and another in 2006). The band reunited again in 2009, this time without Pintado, who had died three years earlier. He is the Arnold. He is terminator.\n\n==History==\nThe group released its debut album, ''[[World Downfall]]'', in 1989.<ref name=\"LarkinHM\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Guinness Who\u2019s Who of Heavy Metal]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Guinness Publishing]]|date=1995|edition=Second|isbn=0-85112-656-1|page=357}}</ref> It is seen as one of the classics of early grindcore.<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r19881|pure_url=yes}} World Downfall - Terrorizer | AllMusic<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> An album containing two rehearsal sessions of the band from 1987 was released in 2003.\n\nThe band split around 1990 when Vincent offered Sandoval a spot in [[Morbid Angel]], while Pintado was being courted to join [[Napalm Death]]; Sandoval saw Terrorizer stagnating, while Morbid Angel and Napalm Death at the time were rapidly gaining popularity. As a result, only Garcia remained; Garcia claims not to have talked to Sandoval since.<ref name=\"sttg\">{{Cite web| title = Slave to the Grind | publisher = Death by Digital| year = 2019 | url = https://reelhouse.org/deathbydigital/slave-to-the-grind/slave-to-the-grind }}</ref>\n\nIn early 2005, it was rumored that Terrorizer were to reform with their original line-up; however, of the original line up, only Jesse Pintado and Pete Sandoval returned. The band released its second studio album, ''[[Darker Days Ahead]]'', in August 2006, on [[Century Media Records]]. Tony Norman (Morbid Angel) joined on guitar and bass, and Anthony Rezhawk joined as the new vocalist. Pintado had been recording and playing shows with Rezhawk's band Resistant Culture and asked him to join Terrorizer. In the week of the album's release, Pintado died due to complications arising from liver failure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thegauntlet.com/article/1510/5626/%09%09%09Terrorizer.html|title=The Gauntlet - Jesse Pintado's Family Comments On His Passing|website=Thegauntlet.com|accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Terrorizer released a new demo track, \"Hordes of Zombies\", on its MySpace page.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blabbermouth.net/news/terrorizer-new-demo-track-posted-online/|title=TERRORIZER: New Demo Track Posted Online|date=June 3, 2009|website=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref> In June 2011, Terrorizer signed to [[Season of Mist]], and released its third album, ''[[Hordes of Zombies]]'', on February 28, 2012.<ref>[http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=74198 Terrorizer Completes New Album \"Hordes Of Zombies\"], Metalunderground.com</ref> Resistant Culture guitarist Katina Culture replaced Pintado and David Vincent rejoined on bass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/terrorizer-signs-with-season-of-mist-new-album-in-the-works/|title=TERRORIZER Signs With SEASON OF MIST; New Album In The Works|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, drummer [[Pete Sandoval]] announced that Terrorizer started writing new material for their next album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/terrorizer-ex-morbid-angel-drummer-pete-sandoval-my-recovery-is-almost|title=Terrorizer/Ex-Morbid Angel Drummer Pete Sandoval: 'My Recovery Is Almost 100%'|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]}}</ref> The fourth album titled ''Caustic Attack'' was released in the fall of 2018 under The End Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/terrorizer-to-release-caustic-attack-album-in-the-fall/|title=TERRORIZER To Release 'Caustic Attack' Album In The Fall|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Terrorizer LA==\n{{main|Terrorizer LA}}\nIn 2014, Oscar Garcia was invited by Jesse Pintado\u2019s sister to put together a new lineup of Terrorizer (his version known as [[Terrorizer LA]] or TLA) for a festival celebrating what would have been Jesse Pintado\u2019s 45th birthday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.laweekly.com/celebrating-terrorizers-legacy-25-years-later/|title=Celebrating Terrorizer's Legacy, 25 Years Later|first=Jason|last=Roche|date=July 9, 2014|website=Laweekly.com|accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/oscar-garcia-and-terrorizer-l-a-to-play-world-downfall-in-its-entirety-at-grindcore-2014-this-july-wehrmacht-nausea-and-more-also-confirmed|title=Oscar Garcia And TERRORIZER L.A. To Play World Downfall In It's Entirety At Grindcore 2014 This July; WEHRMACHT, NAUSEA And More Also Confirmed|website=Bravewords.com|accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref> He asked fellow Nausea member [[Leon del Muerte]] ([[Murder Construct]]) to play guitar, and shortly afterward Cosmo Reveles, Rick Cortez ([[Sadistic Intent]]) and Mike Caffell (Dreaming Dead, Exhausted Prayer) were recruited to fill out the band. The band continues to play under the Terrorizer LA name.\n\n''Before The Downfall,'' a collection of demos and unreleased material, was released by FOAD Records in 2015.\n\n==Band members==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Current\n* [[Pete Sandoval]] \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]] <small>(1986\u20131989, 2005\u20132006, 2009-present)</small>\n* Sam Molina \u2013 [[Bass guitar|bass]], [[Death growl|vocals]] <small>(2013\u2013present)</small>\n* Lee Harrison \u2013 [[Electric guitar|guitar]]s <small>(2013\u2013present)</small>\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n;Former\n* Oscar Garcia \u2013 vocals <small>(1986\u20131989)</small> guitar <small>(1987\u20131989)</small>\n* Alfred \"Garvey\" Estrada \u2013 bass <small>(1986\u20131988)</small>\n* [[Jesse Pintado]] \u2013 guitars <small>(1986\u20131989, 2005\u20132006; his death)</small>\n* Tony Norman \u2013 bass <small>(2005\u20132006, 2009\u20132011)</small>\n* [[David Vincent]] \u2013 bass <small>(1989, 2011\u20132013)</small>\n* Anthony Rezhawk \u2013 vocals <small>(2005\u20132006, 2009\u20132013)</small>\n* Katina Culture \u2013 guitars <small>(2009\u20132013)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Timeline===\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize  = width:900  height:auto  barincrement:20\nPlotArea   = left:110  bottom:75  top:1  right:20\nAlignbars  = justify\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/01/1986 till:{{#time:d/m/Y}}\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nScaleMinor = increment:1  start:1987\nScaleMajor = increment:2  start:1986\nLegend     = position:bottom  orientation:vertical  columns:3\n\nColors =\n  id:vocals   value:red        legend:Vocals\n  id:guitar   value:green      legend:Guitars\n  id:bass     value:blue       legend:Bass\n  id:drums    value:orange     legend:Drums\n  id:album    value:black      legend:Studio_albums\n  id:bars     value:gray(0.9)\n  id:other    value:gray(0.6)  legend:Other_Releases\n\nBackgroundColors =  bars:bars\n\nLineData =\n  at:01/06/1988  color:other  layer:back\n  at:13/11/1989  color:album  layer:back\n  at:22/08/2006  color:album  layer:back\n  at:28/02/2012  color:album  layer:back\n  at:12/09/2018  color:album  layer:back\n\nBarData =\n  bar:Garcia    text:\"Oscar Garcia\"\n  bar:Rezhawk   text:\"Anthony Rezhawk\"\n  bar:Molina    text:\"Sam Molina\"\n  bar:Pintado   text:\"Jesse Pintado\"\n  bar:Culture   text:\"Katina Culture\"\n  bar:Harrison  text:\"Lee Harrison\"\n  bar:Estrada   text:\"Alfred Estrada\" \n  bar:Vincent   text:\"David Vincent\"\n  bar:Norman    text:\"Tony Norman\"\n  bar:Sandoval  text:\"Pete Sandoval\"\n  \nPlotData=\n width:11 textcolor:black align:left anchor:from shift:(11,-4)\n  bar:Garcia      from:01/01/1986  till:01/01/1990  color:vocals\n  bar:Garcia      from:01/01/1986  till:01/02/1989  color:guitar width:3\n  bar:Rezhawk     from:01/01/2005  till:27/08/2006  color:vocals\n  bar:Rezhawk     from:01/01/2009  till:01/01/2013  color:vocals\n  bar:Molina      from:01/01/2013  till:end         color:vocals\n  bar:Molina      from:01/01/2013  till:end         color:bass width:3\n  bar:Pintado     from:01/01/1986  till:01/01/1990  color:guitar\n  bar:Pintado     from:01/01/2005  till:27/08/2006  color:guitar\n  bar:Culture     from:01/01/2009  till:01/01/2013  color:guitar\n  bar:Harrison    from:01/01/2013  till:end         color:guitar\n  bar:Estrada     from:01/01/1986  till:01/02/1989  color:bass\n  bar:Vincent     from:01/02/1989  till:01/01/1990  color:bass\n  bar:Norman      from:01/01/2005  till:27/08/2006  color:bass\n  bar:Norman      from:01/01/2009  till:01/01/2011  color:bass\n  bar:Vincent     from:01/01/2011  till:01/01/2013  color:bass\n  bar:Sandoval    from:01/01/1986  till:01/01/1990  color:drums\n  bar:Sandoval    from:01/01/2005  till:27/08/2006  color:drums\n  bar:Sandoval    from:01/01/2009  till:end         color:drums\n}}\n\n==Discography==\n;Studio albums\n*''[[World Downfall]]'' (1989)\n*''[[Darker Days Ahead]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Hordes of Zombies]]'' (2012)\n*''Caustic Attack'' (2018)\n\n;Split releases\n*''Terrorizer / Nausea'' (1988)\n\n;Demos\n*''Nightmares'' (1987)\n*''Demo '87'' (1988)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.terrorizergrindcore.net/ Official website]\n*[https://www.myspace.com/terrorizergrindcore Official MySpace] includes memorial to Jesse Pintado\n\n{{Terrorizer}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1986 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:American grindcore musical groups]]\n[[Category:Century Media Records artists]]\n[[Category:Death metal musical groups from California]]\n[[Category:Deathgrind musical groups]]\n[[Category:Earache Records artists]]\n[[Category:Hardcore punk groups from California]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1986]]\n[[Category:Musical groups reestablished in 2009]]\n[[Category:Musical trios]]\n[[Category:Political music]]\n[[Category:Season of Mist artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the UK-based extreme music magazine|Terrorizer (magazine)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Terrorizer\n| image            =\n| caption          =\n| image_size       =\n| background       = group_or_band\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Grindcore]]\n* [[deathgrind]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exclaim.ca/music/article/metal_hardcore_2012_year_of_grindcore|title=Metal and Hardcore 2012: The Year of Grindcore|website=Exclaim.ca}}</ref>}}\n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| years_active     = {{flatlist|\n* 1986\u20131989\n* 2005\u20132006\n* 2009\u2013present}}\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Earache Records|Earache]]\n* [[Season of Mist]]\n* [[Century Media Records|Century Media]]\n* [[Relativity Records|Relativity]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Morbid Angel]]\n* [[Napalm Death]]\n* [[Nausea (band, Los Angeles)| Nausea LA]]\n* [[Monstrosity (band)|Monstrosity]]}}\n| website          = http://www.terrorizergrindcore.net/\n| current_members  = [[Pete Sandoval]]<br>Sam Molina<br>Lee Harrison\n| past_members     = Oscar Garcia<br>[[Jesse Pintado]]<br>Alfred \"Garvey\" Estrada<br>Tony Norman<br>Anthony Rezhawk<br>Katina Culture<br>[[David Vincent]]\n}}\n\n'''Terrorizer''' is an American [[grindcore]]<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p14469|pure_url=yes}} Terrorizer | AllMusic<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> band formed in 1986 in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], United States. After disbanding, its members gained recognition by playing in influential [[extreme metal]] bands, such as [[Morbid Angel]] ([[David Vincent]], [[Pete Sandoval]]), [[Napalm Death]] ([[Jesse Pintado]]) and [[Nausea (band, Los Angeles)|Nausea]] (Oscar Garcia, Alfred \"Garvey\" Estrada). To date, Terrorizer has released four studio albums, and broken up twice (once in 1989 and another in 2006). The band reunited again in 2009, this time without Pintado, who had died three years earlier.\n\n==History==\nThe group released its debut album, ''[[World Downfall]]'', in 1989.<ref name=\"LarkinHM\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Guinness Who\u2019s Who of Heavy Metal]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Guinness Publishing]]|date=1995|edition=Second|isbn=0-85112-656-1|page=357}}</ref> It is seen as one of the classics of early grindcore.<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r19881|pure_url=yes}} World Downfall - Terrorizer | AllMusic<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> An album containing two rehearsal sessions of the band from 1987 was released in 2003.\n\nThe band split around 1990 when Vincent offered Sandoval a spot in [[Morbid Angel]], while Pintado was being courted to join [[Napalm Death]]; Sandoval saw Terrorizer stagnating, while Morbid Angel and Napalm Death at the time were rapidly gaining popularity. As a result, only Garcia remained; Garcia claims not to have talked to Sandoval since.<ref name=\"sttg\">{{Cite web| title = Slave to the Grind | publisher = Death by Digital| year = 2019 | url = https://reelhouse.org/deathbydigital/slave-to-the-grind/slave-to-the-grind }}</ref>\n\nIn early 2005, it was rumored that Terrorizer were to reform with their original line-up; however, of the original line up, only Jesse Pintado and Pete Sandoval returned. The band released its second studio album, ''[[Darker Days Ahead]]'', in August 2006, on [[Century Media Records]]. Tony Norman (Morbid Angel) joined on guitar and bass, and Anthony Rezhawk joined as the new vocalist. Pintado had been recording and playing shows with Rezhawk's band Resistant Culture and asked him to join Terrorizer. In the week of the album's release, Pintado died due to complications arising from liver failure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thegauntlet.com/article/1510/5626/%09%09%09Terrorizer.html|title=The Gauntlet - Jesse Pintado's Family Comments On His Passing|website=Thegauntlet.com|accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Terrorizer released a new demo track, \"Hordes of Zombies\", on its MySpace page.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blabbermouth.net/news/terrorizer-new-demo-track-posted-online/|title=TERRORIZER: New Demo Track Posted Online|date=June 3, 2009|website=Blabbermouth.net|accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref> In June 2011, Terrorizer signed to [[Season of Mist]], and released its third album, ''[[Hordes of Zombies]]'', on February 28, 2012.<ref>[http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=74198 Terrorizer Completes New Album \"Hordes Of Zombies\"], Metalunderground.com</ref> Resistant Culture guitarist Katina Culture replaced Pintado and David Vincent rejoined on bass.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/terrorizer-signs-with-season-of-mist-new-album-in-the-works/|title=TERRORIZER Signs With SEASON OF MIST; New Album In The Works|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, drummer [[Pete Sandoval]] announced that Terrorizer started writing new material for their next album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/terrorizer-ex-morbid-angel-drummer-pete-sandoval-my-recovery-is-almost|title=Terrorizer/Ex-Morbid Angel Drummer Pete Sandoval: 'My Recovery Is Almost 100%'|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]}}</ref> The fourth album titled ''Caustic Attack'' was released in the fall of 2018 under The End Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/terrorizer-to-release-caustic-attack-album-in-the-fall/|title=TERRORIZER To Release 'Caustic Attack' Album In The Fall|website=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Terrorizer LA==\n{{main|Terrorizer LA}}\nIn 2014, Oscar Garcia was invited by Jesse Pintado\u2019s sister to put together a new lineup of Terrorizer (his version known as [[Terrorizer LA]] or TLA) for a festival celebrating what would have been Jesse Pintado\u2019s 45th birthday.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.laweekly.com/celebrating-terrorizers-legacy-25-years-later/|title=Celebrating Terrorizer's Legacy, 25 Years Later|first=Jason|last=Roche|date=July 9, 2014|website=Laweekly.com|accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bravewords.com/news/oscar-garcia-and-terrorizer-l-a-to-play-world-downfall-in-its-entirety-at-grindcore-2014-this-july-wehrmacht-nausea-and-more-also-confirmed|title=Oscar Garcia And TERRORIZER L.A. To Play World Downfall In It's Entirety At Grindcore 2014 This July; WEHRMACHT, NAUSEA And More Also Confirmed|website=Bravewords.com|accessdate=November 25, 2019}}</ref> He asked fellow Nausea member [[Leon del Muerte]] ([[Murder Construct]]) to play guitar, and shortly afterward Cosmo Reveles, Rick Cortez ([[Sadistic Intent]]) and Mike Caffell (Dreaming Dead, Exhausted Prayer) were recruited to fill out the band. The band continues to play under the Terrorizer LA name.\n\n''Before The Downfall,'' a collection of demos and unreleased material, was released by FOAD Records in 2015.\n\n==Band members==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Current\n* [[Pete Sandoval]] \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]] <small>(1986\u20131989, 2005\u20132006, 2009-present)</small>\n* Sam Molina \u2013 [[Bass guitar|bass]], [[Death growl|vocals]] <small>(2013\u2013present)</small>\n* Lee Harrison \u2013 [[Electric guitar|guitar]]s <small>(2013\u2013present)</small>\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n;Former\n* Oscar Garcia \u2013 vocals <small>(1986\u20131989)</small> guitar <small>(1987\u20131989)</small>\n* Alfred \"Garvey\" Estrada \u2013 bass <small>(1986\u20131988)</small>\n* [[Jesse Pintado]] \u2013 guitars <small>(1986\u20131989, 2005\u20132006; his death)</small>\n* Tony Norman \u2013 bass <small>(2005\u20132006, 2009\u20132011)</small>\n* [[David Vincent]] \u2013 bass <small>(1989, 2011\u20132013)</small>\n* Anthony Rezhawk \u2013 vocals <small>(2005\u20132006, 2009\u20132013)</small>\n* Katina Culture \u2013 guitars <small>(2009\u20132013)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Timeline===\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize  = width:900  height:auto  barincrement:20\nPlotArea   = left:110  bottom:75  top:1  right:20\nAlignbars  = justify\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/01/1986 till:{{#time:d/m/Y}}\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\nScaleMinor = increment:1  start:1987\nScaleMajor